WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.320
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of the scene in the unseen, I have a recommendation for

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:13.480
[Amit Varma]: you. Do check out Pulya Bazi, hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane, two really good

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:18.680
[Amit Varma]: friends of mine. Kickass podcast in Hindi. It's amazing.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:23.680
[Amit Varma]: Why are there no good people in Indian politics? That's a question I often hear. And much of

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:28.920
[Amit Varma]: the time, it's a rhetorical question, a lament. I attempted an explanation for this in a column

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:33.580
[Amit Varma]: a few months ago, through the lens of economics, as you'd expect, looking at the incentives

00:00:33.580 --> 00:00:37.480
[Amit Varma]: of leaders through the ages. We had great leaders during our freedom struggle because

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:42.640
[Amit Varma]: the men and women who stepped forward had little chance of acquiring any kind of power

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:48.080
[Amit Varma]: or personal glory, and were instead animated by ideals and principles and similar silly

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:53.240
[Amit Varma]: little things that are missing in modern politics. The politician today, on the other hand, seems

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:58.680
[Amit Varma]: motivated only by the lust for power, by the desire to be part of the parasitic rent-seeking

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:03.560
[Amit Varma]: apparatus of government, by the desire to rule rather than serve. Political parties

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:09.240
[Amit Varma]: today are like rival mafias competing for the levers of power. And in these circumstances,

00:01:09.240 --> 00:01:13.600
[Amit Varma]: most self-respecting people stay the hell away from politics. This does not mean that

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:18.960
[Amit Varma]: all politicians are bad people, just that it becomes almost impossible for even a good

00:01:18.960 --> 00:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: person in Indian politics, once she has entered the fray, to do good things. This is not just

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:29.120
[Amit Varma]: because of the incentives that draw people to politics, but also the nature of the political

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:35.720
[Amit Varma]: economy, which almost seems designed, sometimes, to paralyze action. So what do we do? The

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:41.080
[Amit Varma]: incentives of politics are morally corrosive. The circumstances of politics require virtue

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:46.640
[Amit Varma]: to be cast aside. Does that mean that there is no cause for hope in Indian politics? That's

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:51.360
[Amit Varma]: usually my default position. But at the end of recording the episode you are about to

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:57.120
[Amit Varma]: listen to, I had reason to be a little less cynical. I hope you are as inspired as I was

00:01:57.120 --> 00:01:58.120
[Amit Varma]: at the end of it.

