00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:35.080
[Guest]: JP, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you, Amit. My pleasure to be with you. The

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:39.400
[Amit Varma]: last time we spoke almost a couple of years back in episode 50 of the scene in the unseen,

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:44.040
[Amit Varma]: in fact, and I was glad that I had someone like you to bring that number up. It was a

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:48.080
[Amit Varma]: very different show. I did much shorter conversations, our conversation was something like 40 minutes

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:53.200
[Amit Varma]: over a phone. And, you know, over a period of time, the show has evolved to much longer,

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:59.200
[Amit Varma]: discursive, relaxed conversation. So I want to, you know, start this off, not by, you

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:02.760
[Amit Varma]: know, asking you the typical questions everyone will ask you about Indian politics, and where

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:07.760
[Amit Varma]: are we and so on and so forth. But tell me something about your personal journey. Like

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:11.080
[Amit Varma]: where did you grow up? Where was your childhood? What was that like?

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:15.240
[Guest]: Amit, first of all, it's amazing to me that you could actually have a podcast running

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:21.080
[Guest]: into a couple of hours and a very relaxed conversation because in this time and age,

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:26.200
[Guest]: everybody tells you that people have no patience beyond 10 seconds. So it's actually quite

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:30.040
[Guest]: stunning to me that something like this is working and I must congratulate you on the

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:39.120
[Guest]: team. My journey is pretty normal, very ordinary. I grew up in a village. My parents were in

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:44.480
[Guest]: Maharashtra. My father was engaged in the railways in a small little town in Maharashtra.

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:49.920
[Guest]: But because we're of Telugu speaking origin, my parents decided to send me to my mother's

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:55.880
[Guest]: village, where there was a school. My father's village didn't have a school, didn't have

00:05:55.880 --> 00:06:02.960
[Guest]: a high school. So I think I studied there for eight years, though I joined in class

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:08.080
[Guest]: one and some early promotions and all that. So my whole universe at the time was that

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:14.160
[Guest]: village and the school and what little you learn from the school textbooks. Beyond that,

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:18.280
[Guest]: I don't think I had any idea what was happening. Maybe one knew the name of the chief minister

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:25.000
[Guest]: or education minister, but what it meant also, I don't think I really understood. The normal

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:29.500
[Guest]: talk about freedom struggle, very panegyric kind of thing, you know, we read in textbooks

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:35.400
[Guest]: and stuff like that. And some notions of patriotism without understanding what it really means.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:42.280
[Guest]: I suppose mostly idolatrous patriotism, Bharat Mata kind of a thing. Then I went to a Jesuit

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:47.640
[Guest]: college for plus two, what we call college in this part of the country. After 10th grade,

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:53.760
[Guest]: you have to do two years of plus two course. That was a Jesuit college in Vijayawada, a

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:59.240
[Guest]: neighboring town, a significant town, not obviously not a big city, but a significant

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:06.080
[Guest]: town for us, a big city in those days. That college opened up my eyes quite a bit because

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:10.560
[Guest]: you're for the first time exposed to people from all over the Telugu land, some even from

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:15.400
[Guest]: other states. I remember some friends from Kerala and quite a few from Hyderabad and

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:21.640
[Guest]: elsewhere. So your world is a little wider, beginning to understand what the world is

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:25.280
[Guest]: like. At the age of 13, I was there for two, two and a half years because I did two years

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:30.240
[Guest]: course. And then before joining medicine, I continued because there was a delay in admission.

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:37.160
[Guest]: Then medical school, again, another town quite close within another 20, 30 kilometers from

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:45.720
[Guest]: there. Probably at the age of about 16 or so, my world began to open up. So it's curious

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:52.040
[Guest]: that now you have this podcast. I have great fascination for radio because much of my young

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:59.800
[Guest]: adult life was spent on radio. I listened to BBC probably about eight to 10 hours a

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:05.320
[Guest]: day. This was back in the village or when you were in the college. Once I went to college,

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:11.000
[Guest]: maybe once I was about 16 years of age or 15 years of age, I procured a transistor radio

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:17.280
[Guest]: and then I listened. In fact, almost everything that I knew about the world, I picked up from

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:23.900
[Guest]: the BBC, BBC radio in those days. Probably there was a time and there was nothing that

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:26.640
[Guest]: happened anywhere in the world that I did not know within half an hour because I was

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:34.060
[Guest]: listening every half hour, every hour, all kinds of programs. And it was an amazing experience.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest]: The least costly experience to get some modicum of understanding of what's happening. 72 American

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:46.480
[Guest]: presidential elections I remember I followed very closely. Every single state, the primaries

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:54.600
[Guest]: and then the election, et cetera. Then the Watergate, blow by blow. On an hourly basis,

00:08:54.600 --> 00:09:01.520
[Guest]: I knew what was happening. Again, thanks to BBC. Around the same time, if you recall in

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:05.800
[Guest]: the seventies, the anti-corruption movement in India, some amount of unrest and anger

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:11.960
[Guest]: from the youth, because we already finished about 25 years of freedom. There was some

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:19.840
[Guest]: amount of frustration creeping in and therefore Gujarat and then JP's movement in Bihar then

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:24.440
[Guest]: spread to the whole country. I was one of those hundreds of thousands of Indians, young

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:32.240
[Guest]: Indians, deeply impacted by that. Then emergency came again. I was following Allahabad high

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:39.960
[Guest]: court proceedings, blow by blow. So probably most of my life was about what's happening

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:44.200
[Guest]: around me rather than my medical education or something that I was paying enough attention

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:49.000
[Guest]: to be able to understand what the profession is about and acquire some skills. But basically

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:57.040
[Guest]: it was about the world. Emergency changed life. Many of us, for me, certainly, I was

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:06.160
[Guest]: angered. I was deeply disappointed and I was rebellious. How old were you then? 1975, I

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:13.360
[Guest]: was 19 years old, 19 years old. And I very vocally opposed emergency. Wherever there

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:20.880
[Guest]: was an opportunity, extremely vocally I opposed emergency. And I led some small teams of protest,

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:24.800
[Guest]: not on the street. I was never for street marches and stuff like that, but going to

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:31.160
[Guest]: the officials and giving a signed petition and that sort of a thing. Apparently, I didn't

00:10:31.160 --> 00:10:35.920
[Guest]: know at that time, I knew later, I was kept under surveillance. They felt I was sufficient

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:41.400
[Guest]: nuisance to be able to keep track of me. But I was pretty inconsequential. And therefore

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:45.800
[Guest]: there was no reason to arrest me. So I was somewhere in between. I got to know about

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:51.840
[Guest]: that later when I got into the civil services, because there was a delay in the invitation

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:56.240
[Guest]: to join the National Academy. The results were published and all that. I got a pretty

00:10:56.240 --> 00:11:02.440
[Guest]: decent position. I was surprised. I got to know later because the police clearance took

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:09.480
[Guest]: time because of the surveillance earlier. Then after I finished medicine, medicine of

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:13.880
[Guest]: course is a different world altogether. Therefore, you have a, you acquire an understanding of

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:18.800
[Guest]: the society as it is, because the sickness and the causes of sickness, not everything

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:23.400
[Guest]: is really medical. It's actually more about the way we structured our society, your drinking

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:27.320
[Guest]: water, your sanitation, your mosquito control, your infections, and so on and so forth, your

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:34.720
[Guest]: immunization, so on and so forth. That deepened the perception about the country and its governance.

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:41.640
[Guest]: First emergency, there was so much affiliation followed by very quick dejection. That's when

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:45.800
[Guest]: somebody suggested to me, why don't you join the civil services? You're very anguished.

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:50.880
[Guest]: You're obviously not looking for a traditional career as a doctor. You're worried about the

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:57.720
[Guest]: country. Just then, doctors were allowed to join the civil services. Until that time,

00:11:57.720 --> 00:12:01.480
[Guest]: doctors are prohibited for some strange reason in this country. Who knows what the reasons

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:06.080
[Guest]: are? I mean, it doesn't have to be very logical, but they simply said doctors are banned. But

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:13.920
[Guest]: the ban was lifted. Then I joined the civil service. But by the time, I think I was pretty

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:20.880
[Guest]: clear what my goal in life is. Not a career, not a job, but an opportunity to actually

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:27.320
[Guest]: try and make the democracy work the way it should. Because those years, between 1973

00:12:27.320 --> 00:12:36.600
[Guest]: and 1977, let us say, or maybe even post 77, 78, 79, because until we understood the crisis

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:41.880
[Guest]: after Janata's success, I don't think I understood the nature of governance crisis. Otherwise,

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:46.160
[Guest]: I thought Indira Gandhi was the problem. Once she's removed and Janata came to power, things

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:51.680
[Guest]: would be fantastic. That was the notion. So I say, I suppose I also had to see the failure

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:56.600
[Guest]: of Janata to understand it's a deeper crisis than an individual. So since then, I've been

00:12:56.600 --> 00:13:01.800
[Guest]: pretty clear that we have to make our democracy work and we can make it work if we really

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:06.920
[Guest]: design it a little better. And all my life in government and out of government has been

00:13:06.920 --> 00:13:08.680
[Amit Varma]: a quest for that.

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:13.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's this famous essay by the philosopher Thomas Nagel on with the title

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:18.600
[Amit Varma]: of something like what is it like to be a bat, where he essentially postulates that

00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:23.800
[Amit Varma]: a bat experiences the world so differently from human beings, in terms of using echolocation

00:13:23.800 --> 00:13:28.080
[Amit Varma]: instead of sight, and so on and so forth, that we cannot possibly get inside the head

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:31.840
[Amit Varma]: of a bat, it is impossible to understand that. And just thinking aloud, you know, when you

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:36.360
[Amit Varma]: were talking of sort of growing up in your village, and when I even look back at myself

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:42.560
[Amit Varma]: growing up in the 1980s, and so on in relatively privileged circumstances, it strikes me that

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:50.120
[Amit Varma]: young people of today can have no possible conception of the influences that young people

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:55.320
[Amit Varma]: of today can access all the knowledge in the world, they get information from various sources,

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:59.720
[Amit Varma]: there is so much culture coming at them, everything is accessible. When I was growing up in the

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:04.160
[Amit Varma]: 80s, you know, if you wanted specific kinds of international music, you had very little

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:08.080
[Amit Varma]: available to you, you had to, I mean, just getting a mixtape of the music you wanted

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:13.840
[Amit Varma]: was such a remarkable personal triumph, and a triumph of discovery. And in your case,

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:18.520
[Amit Varma]: it's you know, you kind of grow up in a village, and then you go to medical college, but you

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:24.560
[Amit Varma]: have access to the BBC, and there's a sort of a world of information. And it just strikes

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:31.200
[Amit Varma]: me how we are shaped by the contingency of the influences that are available to us. And

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:36.240
[Amit Varma]: it then strikes me that at a wider level, you know, even our society and politics is

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:42.040
[Amit Varma]: perhaps changed by this, because I imagine not everyone in your generation is sort of

00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:46.400
[Amit Varma]: listening to the BBC or has a kind of wonkish interest in American politics that you do,

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:52.520
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, that sort of broader interest. So I imagine in that sense, you were an outlier.

00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:57.480
[Amit Varma]: Can you tell me a little bit about what are the things that young people were into in

00:14:57.480 --> 00:15:02.120
[Amit Varma]: those days? Where did they get the influences from? Were there political instincts, the

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:06.520
[Amit Varma]: typical tribal or communitarian instincts that you get from around you? Was there sort

00:15:06.520 --> 00:15:09.720
[Amit Varma]: of deeper engagement? Where do you get your ideas from?

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:15.920
[Guest]: I think there were several strands, if I may conjecture. One is the kind of thing, very

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:20.520
[Guest]: traditional kind of thing, freedom struggle, romantic notions of the nation and Bharat

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:26.680
[Guest]: Mata and very romantic idealism without any deep understanding and so on and so forth,

00:15:26.680 --> 00:15:32.760
[Guest]: without any exposure. The second is people with slightly more exposed background in cities

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:37.440
[Guest]: and so on and so forth with greater understanding of economic activity. I think by the time

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:43.160
[Guest]: there was a beginning of anger against socialism, just the beginning. It didn't get mature because

00:15:43.160 --> 00:15:48.400
[Guest]: even Lok Naik, JP, all his demands were to make socialism work better. It was not really

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:52.960
[Guest]: about the role of the state clearly defined and so on and so forth. But I could see at

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:56.960
[Guest]: least in my medical school, quite a few. And at the time, because I was not exposed to

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:02.480
[Guest]: that and I didn't understand enough, I was both curious and surprised, because that was

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:08.000
[Guest]: heterodox at the time. The third is a strong ideological thing, right

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:15.680
[Guest]: or wrong. The leftist movement had a profound impact on the psyche. Lots of discussions,

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:22.880
[Guest]: literature, debates, the media, and many colleges had that impact too, sometimes with some understanding,

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:27.760
[Guest]: sometimes without much understanding, sometimes tribalism, sometimes based on ideas. Then

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:35.920
[Guest]: at a global level, Vietnam War during my early youth was a profound influence. It's very

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:41.200
[Guest]: difficult for people of this generation to even contemplate that it could sway so many

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:46.480
[Guest]: people. I remember when Haiphong blockade was ordered by Nixon. I thought that was the

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:50.920
[Guest]: end of the world. I was shaken beyond belief. I was horrified that something like that could

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:55.920
[Guest]: happen. I remember some of my seniors in medical school laughing at me and know because of

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:02.960
[Guest]: my very apoplectic concern, things like that. So that also had some impact. But at least

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:08.080
[Guest]: people of a certain background, the kids who are doing academically reasonably well, etc.

00:17:08.080 --> 00:17:12.040
[Guest]: There was also this relentless focus on their own professional skills and equipping themselves

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:20.080
[Guest]: with knowledge. And what I find is, despite the obvious deprivation at the time, the kids

00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:25.120
[Guest]: then were far more confident about the future, which is amazing. With so few opportunities,

00:17:25.120 --> 00:17:30.400
[Guest]: there was no deep seated insecurity. Whereas today with all the opportunities, I actually

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:37.680
[Guest]: sense a lot more insecurity and a lot more propensity for depression and some disquiet

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:44.080
[Guest]: about the future, which is actually pretty surprising. And of course, in those days,

00:17:44.080 --> 00:17:50.480
[Guest]: the only pastime for my generation was films. Apart from reading books, I used to read a

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:56.280
[Guest]: book a day, some stage of life, all kinds of books, no book a day, my book in two days

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:01.600
[Guest]: was the norm in those days. No, I was so hungry. I was waking up for all the lost time and

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:08.880
[Guest]: I didn't couldn't read much. But that apart only films. Whereas today, I think one disadvantage

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:14.960
[Guest]: that this generation suffers is that there are so many impulses, so many stimuli, that

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:19.880
[Guest]: it's very hard to focus. Your mind cannot be consistently focused on things that really

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:25.000
[Guest]: matter at least in your own mind. But that apart, I don't think that when we grew up,

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.120
[Guest]: we felt there was any sense of deprivation. It's only retrospective, when you look back,

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:31.520
[Guest]: you realize, no, my God, we actually endured all that.

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in fact, one of my friends who was a guest on the show, Suyash Rai, a political

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:40.960
[Amit Varma]: scientist in Delhi, he once theorized that people in the first century AD were much happier

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:45.360
[Amit Varma]: than we are today, to which my response was, how is that possible? There were no smartphones,

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:50.040
[Amit Varma]: there was no air conditioning, how could they be happier, but I guess that's subjective.

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:53.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, you were speaking of reading and you know, like reading a book a day and so

00:18:53.240 --> 00:18:59.480
[Amit Varma]: on, something that you know, I also kind of try to do. And I keep proselytizing the importance

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:03.800
[Amit Varma]: of reading. So I once wrote this column called the Aankho Dekhi Prime Minister. And that

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:08.480
[Amit Varma]: was based on something a friend of Narendra Modi told me about him. And the anecdote was,

00:19:08.480 --> 00:19:13.640
[Amit Varma]: she mentioned how she was a personal friend of Mr. Modi and how she was once sitting with

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:20.040
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Modi at his house, when he was CM of Gujarat. And he was relating this anecdote about how

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:25.040
[Amit Varma]: when he was a kid, his mother was ill. And he went to turn on the fan because she felt

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:29.200
[Amit Varma]: very hot and he flicked the switch on and the fan did not come on because there was

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:34.800
[Amit Varma]: no electricity. And as Modi related the story, his eyes welled up with tears. And the point

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:42.200
[Amit Varma]: my friend was making was that his view of the world, according to her was very experiential,

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:47.720
[Amit Varma]: because he had experienced that lack of electricity and therefore the lack of governance. He then

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:52.040
[Amit Varma]: made it a priority when he came to power to, for example, get power all through Gujarat,

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:57.280
[Amit Varma]: because he understood that. And in her view, his view of politics is very experiential.

00:19:57.280 --> 00:20:01.720
[Amit Varma]: So things that he can experience directly like roads are important. Power is important.

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:06.920
[Amit Varma]: He tries to do cleanliness is important. He tries to do things about that. But a lot of

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:12.600
[Amit Varma]: the business of governance of running an economy rely on abstract concepts that you cannot

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:17.120
[Amit Varma]: experience, like spontaneous order, like, you know, the positive sumness of things,

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:23.480
[Amit Varma]: which is very unintuitive. And therefore, my point was that you have to continuously

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:29.000
[Amit Varma]: read to expand your knowledge of the world, because ultimately, we make sense of the world

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:34.080
[Amit Varma]: by building narratives about it by joining dots, the more dots we have, the clearer our

00:20:34.080 --> 00:20:38.760
[Amit Varma]: pictures. And it seems to me the only way we can accumulate those dots is by reading

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:44.820
[Amit Varma]: not by watching news television or, you know, talking to people on Twitter. So in your experience

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:50.200
[Amit Varma]: through your career, not just in politics, but in the IAS, and so on, do people read

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:55.920
[Amit Varma]: like other understandings of the world ossified from an early age into whatever is received

00:20:55.920 --> 00:21:02.640
[Amit Varma]: wisdom or whatever little scraps they might experience, which caused and I mean, do people

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:06.600
[Amit Varma]: read and would you even say that that's a fundamental problem that people don't read

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:07.600
[Guest]: enough?

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:15.000
[Guest]: It's interesting what you say about Mr. Narendra Modi. Each of us, we will learn about the

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:23.200
[Guest]: world in the early days, only through experience, a child does it. I remember my stupid days,

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:28.440
[Guest]: you know, when I, I didn't have electricity in my home where I grew up with an old aunt

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:33.240
[Guest]: of mine, childhood widow. Again, these are important influences that shape your mind

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:37.440
[Guest]: that a child could be married and she could be a widow and she refused to remarry. You

00:21:37.440 --> 00:21:42.360
[Guest]: understand our society a lot more because it's very real, it's personal. So in order

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:46.240
[Guest]: to understand what electric shock was, I kept hearing about it. I didn't know what it was.

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:54.280
[Guest]: I actually put my finger in that socket and then asked these chaps to switch it on. And

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:59.720
[Guest]: I felt I was shaken. I didn't know it was a shock. How stupid it is. If I have to learn

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:05.600
[Guest]: everything that way, then I think mankind would be particularly tribal. Therefore, this

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:12.160
[Guest]: Prajaksha Pramana as our, our own tradition says this experiential thing, well, it's important.

00:22:12.160 --> 00:22:18.480
[Guest]: Obviously the world grew and became sophisticated and there are so many complex social interactions

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:24.160
[Guest]: and economic interactions because of many other Pramanas. You learn from other's experience.

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest]: That is what humanity is about. An animal learns only from its own experience. Mankind,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.920
[Guest]: because the gift of language, gift of speech, we have the capacity to learn from other's

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:38.600
[Guest]: experience and also pass it on to the next generation. Without that, there's no intellectual

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:44.200
[Guest]: evolution. There's no economic growth. There's no social evolution. Sadly in our country,

00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:50.640
[Guest]: in a substantial measure, you cannot generalize, obviously, there are many, many exceptions.

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:55.280
[Guest]: Education in an insecure society is seen as a passport to employment or some kind of an

00:22:55.280 --> 00:23:02.440
[Guest]: economic prospect. And many, many people after they have arrived, quote unquote, you've got

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:06.920
[Guest]: into IAS, for instance, or you're doing well in a business or a profession or something

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:12.240
[Guest]: else except to the extent that if it's an economically productive business, like, you

00:23:12.240 --> 00:23:16.440
[Guest]: know, you have a medical doctor and you have to be up to date in order to be able to practice

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:22.680
[Guest]: better. Certainly doctors to that extent do try to update their knowledge. If you're a

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:26.120
[Guest]: child accountant and you have to understand what's happening on a day-to-day basis, the

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:31.040
[Guest]: laws and the procedures and so on and so forth. But beyond that, I think the capacity to learn

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:36.400
[Guest]: on a continuing basis and enrich yourself is significantly less in our society than

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:43.320
[Guest]: it should be. For a country of such tremendous depth and strength in our intellectual tradition,

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:50.480
[Guest]: I think this is a serious problem, even in the civil services. And the very lack of specialization,

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:56.280
[Guest]: the notion that almost anybody can do any job in this day and age, that the generalized

00:23:56.280 --> 00:24:05.000
[Guest]: all-purpose service with some vague sense of common sense is enough to really administer

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:10.960
[Guest]: our very complex affairs in the modern world, is absurd. I remember I was appointed as MD

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:16.240
[Guest]: of an apex bank, two apex banks, actually, in the cooperative sector, long term and short

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:22.320
[Guest]: term, in the then combined state of Andhra Pradesh. I knew nothing about banking. Zero.

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:28.120
[Guest]: I was so embarrassed and ashamed. I spent quite a bit of time. Normally I had some humility.

00:24:28.120 --> 00:24:33.000
[Guest]: I tried to learn always whenever I entered a new job from my predecessors. They told

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:37.960
[Guest]: me everything that they thought was relevant, including the cast of each of my senior staff

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:42.520
[Guest]: officers and who is good, who is not good, who is competent, who is corrupt, very valuable

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:47.920
[Guest]: and very accurate by and large. But they forgot to mention or they did not know the two most

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:55.120
[Guest]: important things for those banks at that point of time. The bank, when I joined, had 8% recovery

00:24:55.120 --> 00:25:04.440
[Guest]: rate. Wow. It was after Chaudhary Devilal's loan waiver, 8% recovery rate. As a consequence,

00:25:04.440 --> 00:25:08.920
[Guest]: the bank was the biggest defaulter in India's history to the apex bank, to the national

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:15.560
[Guest]: bank in a part. These are the two most important things for a chief executive to know. I became

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:23.400
[Guest]: the chief executive without knowing that. Now that the bank survived me is a miracle.

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:28.640
[Guest]: But this is our approach in general, perhaps in society and very definitely in governance

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:33.320
[Guest]: in a large measure. I don't think we are doing ourselves a great service by that approach.

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:38.440
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of reading, what was sort of like one question I often ask my guests is if they

00:25:38.440 --> 00:25:43.360
[Amit Varma]: can name one or two or more books which changed the way they think about the world, like books

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:49.400
[Amit Varma]: which sort of gave you that kind of aha moment. Like for me, you know, those aha moments,

00:25:49.400 --> 00:25:53.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, without referring to particular books was, for example, when I understood

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:57.600
[Amit Varma]: how natural selection works, which obviously then, you know, takes away the need to believe

00:25:57.600 --> 00:26:03.000
[Amit Varma]: in God. So that's just an example of one kind of aha moment a person can have or how markets

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:07.480
[Amit Varma]: work or the wonder of spontaneous order and so on. What were your sort of formative aha

00:26:07.480 --> 00:26:13.040
[Amit Varma]: moments and the books or thinkers who gave you those moments who influenced you? Undoubtedly,

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:19.320
[Guest]: the most influential thinkers, thinker early on in my life was Bertrand Russell. See, coming

00:26:19.320 --> 00:26:28.080
[Guest]: from a village background and traditional, normal notions of God and so on and so forth.

00:26:28.080 --> 00:26:33.560
[Guest]: Russell opened my eyes to this whole rational approach, this questioning and a very soothing,

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:41.040
[Guest]: soft, systematic approach to knowledge. To me, it's amazing the way I felt empowered,

00:26:41.040 --> 00:26:44.840
[Amit Varma]: energized by Russell. Is his essay on atheism something you're thinking? A whole lot of

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:50.520
[Guest]: the whole lot of his work. I read several of his works at the time. So it's not one

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:55.760
[Guest]: particular work, but in general, quite a lot, including his biographies and autobiography

00:26:55.760 --> 00:27:02.440
[Guest]: and so on and so forth. The other influences once, you know, I was grounded in some of

00:27:02.440 --> 00:27:07.800
[Guest]: the basics, these things, some of them are fashions of the moment, which I later really

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:15.080
[Guest]: did not take seriously. For instance, now, those days, Albert Camus, kind of things,

00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:19.120
[Guest]: but I don't think they left a profound impact on me, except Camus, the question of myth

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:24.600
[Guest]: of Sisyphus. Now, why? Why the hell are you doing what you're doing? Where do you have

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:30.400
[Guest]: to live? You have to find an answer in life, except that the right question and trying

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:34.960
[Guest]: to find your own answer. I don't think the impact has been very great. But as you said,

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:44.160
[Guest]: it's all evolutionary biology. And increasingly, I find that I'm attracted to anthropology,

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:47.720
[Guest]: how human society has evolved over a period of time. Now, one of the recent books that

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:52.560
[Guest]: impressed me most with the scholarship and insights is Jared Diamond's, Guns, Germs and

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:59.840
[Guest]: Steel, for instance, or even more recent impact would be somebody like Harare, who tried to

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:08.360
[Guest]: make us understand how complex relationships build complex organizations. So there are

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:13.720
[Guest]: many, many people. Increasingly, I find that I don't read fiction these days, almost never.

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:18.040
[Guest]: I read mostly fiction in those days when I read a book a day, both fiction and nonfiction.

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:22.440
[Guest]: But today, it's selective fiction, it has to be economics or governance related or philosophy

00:28:22.440 --> 00:28:29.840
[Guest]: or anthropology or history, biography, things of that kind. And many of you know, as far

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:34.280
[Amit Varma]: as economics and politics are concerned, many of the received notions that you know, even

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:40.160
[Amit Varma]: I got in college, are kind of vaguely left liberal notions, which emphasize the role

00:28:40.160 --> 00:28:45.760
[Amit Varma]: of the state and bringing about welfare and so on and so forth. At what point did you

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:51.720
[Amit Varma]: start thinking differently about economics and even politics, which is, you know, Indian

00:28:51.720 --> 00:28:56.840
[Guest]: politics has such a focus on. It's a very good question. Economics, you know, many of

00:28:56.840 --> 00:29:01.880
[Guest]: my generation, it's very difficult for young people today to understand how seduced we

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:08.160
[Guest]: were by, by the notion of the state being the center of the universe. Socialism, public

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:13.480
[Guest]: sector was natural things. But luckily, while I was also part of that brigade, which broadly

00:29:13.480 --> 00:29:18.960
[Guest]: believed in the goodness of the state and public sector, I was never a Marxist. I don't

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:22.240
[Guest]: even know why probably there was too much of influence of Gandhiji's thinking and the

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:30.400
[Guest]: reverence for Gandhi in me to go for the Marxist doctrine, because the collectivization and

00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:34.280
[Guest]: killing the individual spirit and of course, the violence that was necessary accompaniment

00:29:34.280 --> 00:29:39.920
[Guest]: of the traditional Marxism, I think all those repel me a great deal. But I think the broad

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:49.120
[Guest]: tendency was a little pink. I think that changed dramatically when I became in 1984, Special

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:52.760
[Guest]: Officer of the Visakhapatnam Steel Project. It was then India's largest public sector

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:57.760
[Guest]: undertaking in terms of no investment 8000 crores, big money, then now it doesn't seem

00:29:57.760 --> 00:30:01.320
[Guest]: to be a big money. Billion dollars is not a big money now. But a lot of money at that

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:05.800
[Guest]: time, 8000 crores, then it was probably three, $4 billion. But more important, given India's

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:11.680
[Guest]: kitty, it was a very big sum. Very soon, I realized that public sector in India is private

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:16.640
[Guest]: sector of those in public office. Wow. It has nothing to do with the people of the country,

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:23.240
[Guest]: the word public seduced us. Because words when we use them repetitively, they could

00:30:23.240 --> 00:30:27.600
[Guest]: actually give a different meaning to your mind altogether different from what actually

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:35.960
[Guest]: is reality. So I was shaken. Since then, I've been an implacable supporter of the market,

00:30:35.960 --> 00:30:40.720
[Guest]: wherever market works and competition and choice are possible. And they very clearly

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:44.640
[Guest]: defined limited all of the state, though I always understood the importance of the state.

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:48.840
[Guest]: Therefore, my whole life is about how to make the state work better. So I'm not one of those

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:54.160
[Guest]: would say the market offers all solutions. That's a silly notion. But I always had a

00:30:54.160 --> 00:31:00.040
[Guest]: very clear notion. I remember in 1991, May on the fourth of May, the economist wrote

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:07.520
[Guest]: a brilliant 28 page essay on India, Clive Crook. Till date, I think it's probably the

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:13.760
[Guest]: most insightful, most seminal essay on India. In those days, economic reform did not come

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:18.760
[Guest]: yet. It came two, three months later. In those days, I made hundreds of copies. Those days

00:31:18.760 --> 00:31:22.240
[Guest]: you had to Xerox it. There was no other means no internet, no nothing. We didn't hear this

00:31:22.240 --> 00:31:27.800
[Guest]: expression. You sent links to people by taking physical Xerox. And I sent to prominent editors

00:31:27.800 --> 00:31:31.800
[Guest]: owners of big newspapers, significant people in the country, hoping that they would actually

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:36.200
[Guest]: go through it and then rethink many of their assumptions. So that's the economic thing.

00:31:36.200 --> 00:31:40.600
[Guest]: Since then, I've been absolutely clear. Unless we define the role of the state clearly, and

00:31:40.600 --> 00:31:46.040
[Guest]: unless the state performs that role very well, efficiently and fairly, the economy will be

00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:51.160
[Guest]: in shambles and society will be in shambles. And by expanding your remit and trying to

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:55.760
[Guest]: do everything and doing everything generally badly, we messed up our society and governance.

00:31:55.760 --> 00:32:05.120
[Guest]: I have absolutely no doubt about it. About politics, I think it was the contrast between

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:12.720
[Guest]: what was happening in India and what happened in Nixon, Watergate trials. Relative to what

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:21.680
[Guest]: we were doing to ourselves, Nixon's follies were very marginal. Let's be a little practical

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:27.240
[Guest]: about it. But in those days, like many young people, idealistic, no room for any error,

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:32.480
[Guest]: you have to be absolutely correct and moral kind of a thing. Dogmatically virtuous. Exactly.

00:32:32.480 --> 00:32:36.720
[Guest]: Dogmatically virtuous is the right expression. I, like many other people across the world,

00:32:36.720 --> 00:32:41.040
[Guest]: I'm sure, genuinely believed that Nixon was a terrible creature. In retrospect, I actually

00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:47.440
[Guest]: believe that minus Watergate, he was a pretty good president, a pretty good statesman too.

00:32:47.440 --> 00:32:52.200
[Guest]: But anyway, at the time, the way the system dealt with the infractions of the mightiest

00:32:52.200 --> 00:32:56.360
[Guest]: leader in the country, the whole process, because I was following now the congressional

00:32:56.360 --> 00:33:03.080
[Guest]: hearings, et cetera, on radio, we had no access to TV and TV is not available in India for

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:10.240
[Guest]: most people, most of the time. And that versus what Mrs. Gandhi could do and get away with,

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:15.680
[Guest]: including finally the imposition of emergency and incarceration of 100,000 people, almost

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:20.200
[Guest]: every significant voice in the position. And the contrast was extraordinarily glaring to

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:26.200
[Guest]: me. And I remember in 74, just two days after Nixon resigned, I wrote an editorial for my

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:31.680
[Guest]: college magazine. I was the editor for the English section. Somebody showed it to me

00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:36.560
[Guest]: the other day, some 40 years later. It's pretty much summarizes what I've been doing even

00:33:36.560 --> 00:33:43.520
[Guest]: today, except that it was more breathless and more youthful and maybe a little bit more

00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:49.560
[Guest]: certain. But it was pretty much known by that time. I was pretty clear what was happening.

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:54.840
[Guest]: When I look back, I realized that I am what I was in many ways, then.

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how the timelines work out where you describe your disillusionment

00:33:58.400 --> 00:34:02.520
[Amit Varma]: with politics because of the emergency. But at the same time, you get into the ideas with

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:06.920
[Amit Varma]: a lot of idealism about changing the country. And my father was also an IAS officer and

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:12.360
[Amit Varma]: he describes to me he joined in the mid 60s, 63, 64 sometime around then. And he talks

00:34:12.360 --> 00:34:17.000
[Amit Varma]: about how he joined with so much idealism and wanting to do good for the country, which

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:22.480
[Amit Varma]: I am, of course, skeptical of, because nowadays, we know what the bureaucracy is, and why people

00:34:22.480 --> 00:34:27.760
[Amit Varma]: would want to join the IAS, what those incentives would be. But he kind of retained his idealism

00:34:27.760 --> 00:34:33.320
[Amit Varma]: in a manner of speaking for much longer than one would have expected right to after retirement.

00:34:33.320 --> 00:34:38.120
[Amit Varma]: But in your case, you've already spoken about like one aha moment where you realized that

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:44.200
[Amit Varma]: the public sector is actually the private sector of those in public office. What was

00:34:44.200 --> 00:34:51.240
[Amit Varma]: a process of that idealism turning to cynicism? And therefore, at what point did you begin

00:34:51.240 --> 00:34:56.320
[Amit Varma]: to think that I cannot make the change I want here, I have to get into politics.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:35:01.280
[Guest]: My journey was not of that kind. I didn't join the IAS for a career. I joined for an

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:06.560
[Guest]: opportunity because even by that time, I remember vividly thinking actually, politics is not

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:12.800
[Guest]: an option. Now, when I look back, politics was a much better option than than it is today,

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:17.840
[Guest]: to be truthful. And yet, for my young mind, impressionable mind and seeing the way things

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:24.400
[Guest]: were happening, even by that time, if you're not a person of means or pedigree, and if

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:29.560
[Guest]: you want to stick to certain norms that you imposed on yourself, then political career

00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:36.240
[Guest]: was not an option. I understood that. But here is an option where your ability and hard

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:40.560
[Guest]: work alone can take you don't require anybody's patronage. You don't require to compromise

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:45.280
[Guest]: your moral compass. And I could sense I didn't know, initially exactly what I was looking

00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:51.720
[Guest]: for. But I knew it would afford me an immense opportunity to understand and to make a difference.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:55.920
[Guest]: And I don't think I was disappointed. It certainly gave me a ringside seat and therefore a much

00:35:55.920 --> 00:36:03.280
[Guest]: deeper understanding of our system and society while I worked. And many people believe that

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:08.280
[Guest]: my results were pretty out of the ordinary. And that's because the bar in India is so

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:14.160
[Guest]: low that almost anybody who applies himself or herself a little bit appears to be outstanding.

00:36:14.160 --> 00:36:18.800
[Guest]: I was one of those lucky ones to get the public support and adulation and support of all political

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:24.400
[Guest]: parties. I must also be very fair. While I had my battles, I never took them seriously

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:28.680
[Guest]: in the sense that no, I can't really talk about my God, there was so much pressure on

00:36:28.680 --> 00:36:35.200
[Guest]: me and therefore I had to, there's nothing heroic. I genuinely believe that across the

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:41.080
[Guest]: spectrum, while I had my battles, they all respected me and gave me space and, and therefore

00:36:41.080 --> 00:36:45.120
[Guest]: I could achieve results which were generally regarded as way out of the ordinary and put

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:51.040
[Guest]: in place, no, actually, uh, implement some of my ideas in terms of people's empowerment

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:55.600
[Guest]: in terms of changing the way things work in terms of decentralization of power, designing

00:36:55.600 --> 00:37:00.600
[Guest]: in a manner that incentives are altered, et cetera. All the ideas that I espouse now and

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:06.440
[Guest]: try and work on, I actually could implement wherever it's possible and with exceptional

00:37:06.440 --> 00:37:11.360
[Guest]: results. So mine was not a case of cynicism or frustration on account of non-performance

00:37:11.360 --> 00:37:20.240
[Guest]: or a sense that my hands and feet were tied. It was that I could see that when I'm lionized,

00:37:20.240 --> 00:37:24.920
[Guest]: I could see my performance probably is about 20 or 30 on a scale of a hundred. And because

00:37:24.920 --> 00:37:29.600
[Guest]: in this benighted country, the performance on an average is about five or six, this 20

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:33.760
[Guest]: or 30 is seen as outstanding. I was deeply troubled by that. And I used to say that to

00:37:33.760 --> 00:37:39.880
[Guest]: the public repeatedly on a scale of a hundred, what I'm doing is 2025 and you're so happy

00:37:39.880 --> 00:37:45.120
[Guest]: because now I used to use the expression, Alpa Santos, we are content with so little

00:37:45.120 --> 00:37:49.280
[Guest]: because we don't realize how much more is possible and necessary unless we are habitually

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:55.480
[Guest]: able to do 70 or 80 in a scale of a hundred. Uh, all our individual heroism is of no consequence.

00:37:55.480 --> 00:38:00.760
[Guest]: I was clear enough to understand that it was that that drove me. And once I understood

00:38:00.760 --> 00:38:08.440
[Guest]: that in pretty early on in my, my career, I realized that the bigger change had to happen.

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:13.280
[Guest]: And as I developed that, that thinking and more or less to what required to happen, the

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:19.440
[Guest]: only question is when, not whether. So when I felt that, yes, I mean, I have learned something

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:24.200
[Guest]: that's not enough, but maybe now I have to actually move into a different area now to

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:29.720
[Guest]: try and make those changes happen. That's when I left. It's not cynicism at all.

00:38:29.720 --> 00:38:34.840
[Amit Varma]: In one aspect, it seems to me that your drive in politics to make things better. And as

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:39.320
[Amit Varma]: the imperative that drives you to get into politics in the first place is more reminiscent

00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:44.120
[Amit Varma]: of pre-independence politicians and politicians today, like one lamin that is often made by

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:49.160
[Amit Varma]: people is that look at the quality of leaders and statesmen that we had, uh, you know, in

00:38:49.160 --> 00:38:54.160
[Amit Varma]: the thirties and forties and before that, and contrasted with what we have now. And

00:38:54.160 --> 00:38:59.560
[Amit Varma]: I'd once written a column sort of speculating on why this could be the case. And it struck

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:04.320
[Amit Varma]: me that it, to a certain extent, it might boil down to incentives because if you had

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:09.000
[Amit Varma]: to take part in the freedom struggle at that time, you had virtually no chance of succeeding

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:13.600
[Amit Varma]: or gaining power in a meaningful sense, power over other people. You were driven only by

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:17.960
[Amit Varma]: ideals. You did it because it mattered to you in an idealistic sense, and you would

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:22.800
[Amit Varma]: sacrifice everything for that. You were not out there to make money or exploit other people.

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:27.240
[Amit Varma]: But those incentives have changed today. You know, power does corrupt even the lure of

00:39:27.240 --> 00:39:32.600
[Amit Varma]: power corrupts power and money are in this constant sort of a circle that is vicious

00:39:32.600 --> 00:39:38.640
[Amit Varma]: for the public, certainly. And people are driven by those kinds of wrong incentives

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:43.560
[Amit Varma]: and lust for power, which always, of course, corrodes character. And is that a structural

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:48.600
[Amit Varma]: flaw to which there is no solution? Because looking at our politics, it seems to me and

00:39:48.600 --> 00:39:52.440
[Amit Varma]: I could be wrong, and this could be a naive observation, but it seems to me that you are

00:39:52.440 --> 00:39:58.000
[Guest]: an exception. You're an outlier. I don't agree. There are three strands in this. The first

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:01.760
[Guest]: is I agree that there is an enormous lust for power in our society relative to many

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:06.440
[Guest]: other societies, because we've always been hierarchical society from a family to a nation

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:11.920
[Guest]: from caste system to operation of women. Though there are many virtues in a family, I admire

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:18.440
[Guest]: Indian family structure, but minus this, these negatives, but we are a hierarchical authoritarian

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:24.400
[Guest]: society intuitively. And therefore, this has also spread to the public domain. Therefore,

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:28.800
[Guest]: the lust for power in this country without a sense of purpose is perhaps extraordinary

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:33.800
[Guest]: in this country. I don't think there's another society that matches India in that lust for

00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:39.320
[Guest]: power without purpose. That's a larger cultural problem. But barring that, the rest of your

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:47.040
[Guest]: hypothesis I don't think is valid. One, the politicians today are not evil or bad. I know

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:50.400
[Guest]: this is not a very fashionable statement, but I've been saying this for the past 30,

00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:55.840
[Guest]: 40 years, not today. Many of them, in fact, most of them are pretty well-meaning people

00:40:55.840 --> 00:41:01.120
[Guest]: who want to do something good. They also have this bug that they want glory and they want

00:41:01.120 --> 00:41:04.120
[Guest]: recognition and there's nothing wrong with that. That ambition is not a terrible thing.

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:09.800
[Guest]: Actually, it's a good thing. But sadly, we created an institutional mechanism and incentive

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:17.920
[Guest]: structure where honesty and survival in public office is increasingly incompatible. Even

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:22.600
[Guest]: if individuals are honest, and there are even today, quite a few individuals in public office

00:41:22.600 --> 00:41:28.920
[Guest]: who are pretty honest, institutionally, you cannot be honest and you cannot survive. Dr.

00:41:28.920 --> 00:41:33.680
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh is personally honest. Narendra Modi is personally honest. Many others are

00:41:33.680 --> 00:41:38.280
[Guest]: personally honest. But institutionally, you have to preserve the system of corruption

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:43.240
[Guest]: in order to survive in public office. It's a larger structure and institutional issue

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:46.680
[Guest]: where the victims of a vicious cycle, they're not really villains. Therefore, it will be

00:41:46.680 --> 00:41:53.160
[Guest]: very sad and also counterproductive if we view them all as evil people who are out to

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:57.080
[Guest]: make something. And therefore, they entered public life. Because then the conclusion has

00:41:57.080 --> 00:42:00.880
[Guest]: to be that every panchayat board member to the Prime Minister of India, they come only

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:06.360
[Guest]: with an evil intent. It's not true at all. There is a third dimension to it. We're looking

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:12.480
[Guest]: at only politics as the quest for power, not like Maharashtra, what's happening. This morning

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:16.600
[Guest]: you were telling me about what's happening. I was not aware because I don't watch TV news

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:22.200
[Amit Varma]: or newspapers. We're recording this on Saturday, November 23rd, when, you know, last night

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:26.720
[Amit Varma]: Uddhav Thackeray was supposed to be CM and this morning Mr. Fadnavis has been voted in.

00:42:26.720 --> 00:42:34.000
[Guest]: I had such a hearty laughter that tears rolled down my cheeks. These are the unexpectedly

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:42.320
[Guest]: funny moments in life. But we are forgetting that there's a whole lot more to politics.

00:42:42.320 --> 00:42:46.600
[Guest]: What you and I are doing is politics. You may not contest elections, you may not seek

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:52.600
[Guest]: power, but this politics is small p minus power struggle. I think there are thousands

00:42:52.600 --> 00:42:56.720
[Guest]: of extraordinarily bright people and that number is increasing. I'm delighted to note

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:03.040
[Guest]: that who are deeply concerned about our public space and trying to do something. I've seen

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:07.800
[Guest]: in recent months, for instance, some exceptional people working in the field of education and

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:11.600
[Guest]: not so many in healthcare, but there are quite a few who are doing that. Some in rule of

00:43:11.600 --> 00:43:17.280
[Guest]: law. This is politics. Politics are the best kind. And these are all imbued by the same

00:43:17.280 --> 00:43:23.080
[Guest]: degree of idealism and same kind of idealism that inspired our freedom fighters. So I don't

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:27.960
[Guest]: think that there is a dearth of that. What is the problem is that they have no space

00:43:27.960 --> 00:43:33.640
[Guest]: in impacting decision making. And apart from power struggle, for whatever reason, is it

00:43:33.640 --> 00:43:37.800
[Guest]: because it's not easy or you chose not to be a part of the power struggle, you may not

00:43:37.800 --> 00:43:41.280
[Guest]: want to be in power. That's perfectly all right. But when you have something to offer

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:46.560
[Guest]: to the country, if X is in power, that X must have the wisdom to utilize your talent and

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:52.960
[Guest]: the barriers between the state and the society must not be so rigid. We erected such barriers

00:43:52.960 --> 00:43:59.560
[Guest]: that a third rate buffoon in government treats an exceptional genius who can actually make

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:05.960
[Guest]: a difference to the country as a mendicant, because this genius happens to go to the buffoon.

00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:12.800
[Guest]: But to me, these people are doing politics of the right kind. So while I understand the

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:18.960
[Guest]: anger, the frustration, some amount of despair, it's now universal. And there's not one of

00:44:18.960 --> 00:44:24.640
[Guest]: us, including me, who from time to time does not yield to that. I think there is a lot

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:25.640
[Amit Varma]: of hope.

00:44:25.640 --> 00:44:30.240
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's a very illuminating distinction between electoral politics and the sort of

00:44:30.240 --> 00:44:34.280
[Amit Varma]: politics that we are doing now, for example, by having this conversation. I didn't mean

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:38.640
[Amit Varma]: to imply that politicians today are evil necessarily to use that term, but merely that they're

00:44:38.640 --> 00:44:45.480
[Amit Varma]: responding to incentives that drive their behavior in ways that outside of those incentives

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:51.320
[Amit Varma]: would be considered virtuous, and which brings me to this great dilemma of democracy, this

00:44:51.320 --> 00:44:55.680
[Amit Varma]: interplay between money and power, where we know that listen to win elections, you need

00:44:55.680 --> 00:45:00.700
[Amit Varma]: huge amounts of money, the money has to come from somewhere. Most often, it will come from

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:05.380
[Amit Varma]: interest groups, they will have a quid pro quo built into the system. If it is a specific

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:10.720
[Amit Varma]: industrialist, he will then want that once you come to power, you erect barriers to entry

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:15.320
[Amit Varma]: so that his market is protected, and so on and so forth. And of course, the problem of

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:20.200
[Amit Varma]: special interests in electoral politics is probably far worse in the US than it is here.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:26.080
[Amit Varma]: Here, there are all kinds of, I think, other dynamic factors at play. But is this I mean,

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:31.080
[Amit Varma]: is there a democracy in the world where this is not a problem, where these sort of institutional

00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:36.360
[Amit Varma]: incentives are in play, where the chief incentive for a politician always is listen, I need

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:40.880
[Amit Varma]: to get elected again. And therefore, I need money for my campaign. And therefore, I need

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:45.800
[Amit Varma]: to keep these people happy, not necessarily cater to what might be good governance at

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:55.200
[Amit Varma]: large. But you know, does this necessary interplay between money and power in a democracy, pervert

00:45:55.200 --> 00:46:01.960
[Amit Varma]: our incentives, the incentives of politicians, so much that the kind of politics, you know,

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:07.280
[Amit Varma]: you and I would like to see is effectively, at least very unlikely, if not impossible.

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:11.400
[Guest]: You know, obviously, politics needs money, the moment you want to reach the people make

00:46:11.400 --> 00:46:17.960
[Guest]: people think and communicate and compete, and study and research and come up with alternatives,

00:46:17.960 --> 00:46:22.320
[Guest]: it costs money, no question about it. But that's different from the kind of incentives

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:29.240
[Guest]: that we have in play in this country. It's not true that most mature democracies really

00:46:29.240 --> 00:46:33.400
[Guest]: play by those incentives, even America, which is the worst among the developed countries,

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:37.560
[Guest]: no, almost from the day you are elected, you have to again raise money for the next election,

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:44.600
[Guest]: but just legitimate money for legitimate campaign purposes. While it is sad, some of it could

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:50.720
[Guest]: have been avoided by more sensible approaches. There is no serious compromise in terms of

00:46:50.720 --> 00:46:55.320
[Guest]: public interest, or in terms of ethics and morality. It's easy for us to say in America

00:46:55.320 --> 00:47:00.760
[Guest]: also is like that, which is rubbish, we don't understand at all. Europe is altogether different.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:06.280
[Guest]: They brought the cost very low level, very high quality of discourse and integrity in

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:10.880
[Guest]: public office, not having to worry about raising resources every day for the elected representatives

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:17.800
[Guest]: is pretty strong in that continent. So I don't think it's inevitable that democracy will

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:24.480
[Guest]: degenerate into collecting money and therefore compromising yourself. It is a systemic issue.

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:30.740
[Guest]: And the systems, the consequences are not always universally the same for the same system.

00:47:30.740 --> 00:47:36.640
[Guest]: It depends on the kind of circumstances in which you created a system. I was because

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:43.600
[Guest]: no three days from today, we have the 70th anniversary of our constitution making Dr.

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:53.080
[Guest]: Ambedkar on the 25th of November 1949. He made a very significant speech. He said, Look,

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:56.040
[Guest]: there are three things required just because we made a constitution don't believe that

00:47:56.040 --> 00:48:03.600
[Guest]: everything will be wonderful. The first he said, Let us give up the grammar of anarchy.

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:08.440
[Guest]: He actually coined use that expression, the grammar of anarchy, and use constitutional

00:48:08.440 --> 00:48:14.240
[Guest]: methods of protest in order to pursue the economic and social goals that we have in

00:48:14.240 --> 00:48:19.080
[Guest]: mind. The country ignored that. We continue to pretend as if you know, there are extra

00:48:19.080 --> 00:48:24.760
[Guest]: constitutional methods of obstruction and abuse, which are pretty normal and, and it's

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:29.040
[Guest]: not merely a politician or a political party. We as a culture have never really gotten into

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:38.480
[Guest]: that Ambedkar's mode, what he advised. The second thing Ambedkar said, he said never

00:48:38.480 --> 00:48:44.440
[Guest]: he quoted J.S. Mill, never lay your freedom at the feet of a tyrant, however great the

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:51.480
[Guest]: leader is. You have some restraint, don't have this extraordinary hero worship and learn

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:56.320
[Guest]: to hold them to account. We fail to do that. Our political parties, our family estates,

00:48:56.320 --> 00:49:01.560
[Guest]: you see the leaders, even at an MLA or MP level, let alone a minister or a prime minister's

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:07.400
[Guest]: level, the kind of, you know, the hundreds of people thronging around them, even as in

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:14.000
[Guest]: your mind, you abuse them and you come back and criticize them harshly. This, this desperate

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:22.160
[Guest]: worship of power, not only seeking power for one's own self, but also worship of power.

00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:27.320
[Guest]: We have never really kept it on a leash and therefore the parties decide your fate as

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:34.120
[Guest]: a human being in politics and therefore consequences follow. And the third, he said, we also have

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:39.840
[Guest]: to build a social democracy, particularly emphasize two things in a hierarchical society

00:49:39.840 --> 00:49:45.000
[Guest]: where caste is always distinguished by birth, your superior and inferior, how to address

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:50.880
[Guest]: that and two, how to address the fraternity. One equality. The second is fraternity. See

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:56.640
[Guest]: all these groups, varied groups may be equal, may not be hierarchical, but that language

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:01.840
[Guest]: or region or religion, we all know the strife in the country from time to time, unless that

00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:07.800
[Guest]: fraternity is brought systematically institutionally, there's a problem. But at the heart of it,

00:50:07.800 --> 00:50:14.840
[Guest]: I'm absolutely certain that we have committed grave blunders and believing that vote and

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:22.640
[Guest]: the right to shout are enough to build a democracy. And there I lay the blame at the feet of all

00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:28.600
[Guest]: the great men who built India because they were great men and women, leaders of great

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:35.560
[Guest]: honor and distinction. They assumed that without institutional mechanisms to ensure that degree

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:39.960
[Guest]: of conduct, it would automatically happen because anything else was unthinkable for

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:46.200
[Guest]: them. That was a mistake in not recognizing human nature anywhere in the world and therefore

00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:53.680
[Guest]: not creating an institutional mechanism to make democracy work. In particular, low bureaucracy

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:59.960
[Guest]: in this country is unlike any other low bureaucracy anywhere in the world. It's so powerful, so

00:50:59.960 --> 00:51:06.600
[Guest]: oppressive that the ordinary clock and garment is bigger than 90% of the people. We haven't

00:51:06.600 --> 00:51:11.320
[Guest]: really paused to think about it, what it means and what are the consequences to a democracy

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:17.520
[Guest]: and governance and account of that. And as a result of this unaccountability, the people

00:51:17.520 --> 00:51:21.720
[Guest]: always are mendicants. And of course, the socialist model we adopted early on, the scarcity

00:51:21.720 --> 00:51:26.600
[Guest]: economy and the, and the license permit, Raj, and the begging the garment official for everything

00:51:26.600 --> 00:51:31.520
[Guest]: that you are entitled to get as a human being in your life. That made it even worse. The

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:36.760
[Guest]: roles that reversed mendicant, the citizen became the mendicant, the employee who is a public servant

00:51:36.760 --> 00:51:43.720
[Guest]: became the master. This lack of accountability is a first major brand. We haven't understood

00:51:43.720 --> 00:51:49.720
[Guest]: just because power changed hands, it wouldn't change much. The second thing is we centralized

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:55.740
[Guest]: power abnormally. Despite Mahatma Gandhi's entreaties, we never created a link in people's

00:51:55.740 --> 00:52:00.520
[Guest]: minds between the vote that they give and the consequences to their lives at a personal

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:05.080
[Guest]: and family level. So what is a celebration? All the great things we talk about Indian

00:52:05.080 --> 00:52:10.040
[Guest]: democracy and voting, actually, they're the wrong things that we celebrate. There's so

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:18.200
[Guest]: much of wonder that this is rubbish. This is about our collective goals. There's nothing

00:52:18.200 --> 00:52:24.880
[Guest]: very noble about it. It's very mundane. Water supply, electricity, the sewerage system,

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:30.760
[Guest]: the stormwater drainage, the school functioning for my kids, the local health center, or the

00:52:30.760 --> 00:52:37.280
[Guest]: mosquito control so that I don't get dengue first sign of trouble. So this is very practical.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:43.320
[Guest]: Instead of making it a practical issue, we made it a grand national issue. In the absence

00:52:43.320 --> 00:52:47.480
[Guest]: of decentralization, people never understood the link between these two. We keep voting

00:52:47.480 --> 00:52:52.440
[Guest]: each time with great fanfare and great hope and expectation, and we keep getting disappointed

00:52:52.440 --> 00:52:58.040
[Guest]: almost on each occasion. The third is rule of law. On paper it is there, but in reality

00:52:58.040 --> 00:53:02.640
[Guest]: it stinks. We all know that. Therefore, neither are the rulers held to account, both bureaucratic

00:53:02.640 --> 00:53:09.300
[Guest]: and political, nor are we secure enough to believe that our rights will be enforced.

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:14.760
[Guest]: No matter how big the other fellow is, no matter how small I am, my rights will be enforced

00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:21.680
[Guest]: and I will have my place in the sun. That confidence nobody in India has. And finally,

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:28.560
[Guest]: an electoral system wholly unsuited to our conditions. It's not per se bad, but if conditions

00:53:28.560 --> 00:53:34.000
[Guest]: were right, it would have been okay. But over a period of time, because of the three failings

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:39.760
[Guest]: that I mentioned, electoral system became what by? Because in a poor country where the

00:53:39.760 --> 00:53:43.360
[Guest]: delivery is weak for the reasons I mentioned, where rule of law is not there, accountability

00:53:43.360 --> 00:53:49.520
[Guest]: is not there, people are mendicants, then you know, they're deeply dissatisfied and

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:54.400
[Guest]: we are poor and therefore something tangible that day, that money does matter. Not that

00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:58.160
[Guest]: I vote necessarily for the fellow who gives money, but I do not vote any longer without

00:53:58.160 --> 00:54:01.720
[Guest]: getting the money in my hand in the first place. So the entry barrier is created and

00:54:01.720 --> 00:54:07.880
[Guest]: of course the corruption, so on and so forth. Then the freebies. Now, for instance, many

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:11.240
[Guest]: states where on the verge of a fiscal collapse, the kind of freebies, they've gone out of

00:54:11.240 --> 00:54:15.720
[Guest]: control completely because the parties are desperate. And today I think it's safe to

00:54:15.720 --> 00:54:20.160
[Guest]: say that political parties have come to a stage when if they say, we will not offer

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:26.320
[Guest]: any freebies, they almost certainly get defeated. So it's no longer blaming this part of that,

00:54:26.320 --> 00:54:31.380
[Guest]: but there's a systemic issue. The third is divisions. It's easy in a diverse society

00:54:31.380 --> 00:54:36.320
[Guest]: to fragment us and then fashion vote banks because of the primordial loyalties. These

00:54:36.320 --> 00:54:44.400
[Guest]: are not unusual and these are not unexpected. In fact, there is a logical sequence. And

00:54:44.400 --> 00:54:48.080
[Guest]: now I think we have to fix these first three things. And I think we have to change the

00:54:48.080 --> 00:54:52.920
[Guest]: incentives and electoral system. That's the primary thing. It's not necessary at all for

00:54:52.920 --> 00:54:58.840
[Guest]: a country to degenerate. I would make one postulate. It's a very bold one. You take

00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:05.160
[Guest]: any country, make it a democracy. The way you made India a democracy without these four

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:12.320
[Guest]: things, particularly these three things, centralized power, don't have a real rule of law. Don't

00:55:12.320 --> 00:55:18.600
[Guest]: deliver even the basic services to ordinary citizens in a poor society in general. I guarantee

00:55:18.600 --> 00:55:23.240
[Guest]: you the consequences that followed in India are inevitable in the electoral system that

00:55:23.240 --> 00:55:29.280
[Guest]: we have chosen. There's nothing unique about India. It is almost mathematical.

00:55:29.280 --> 00:55:33.680
[Amit Varma]: There's a lot to unpack in this. And in fact, I'm, I'm looking forward to just sort of listening

00:55:33.680 --> 00:55:38.040
[Amit Varma]: to this episode again and taking notes. I'll, before I sort of move on to my next question,

00:55:38.040 --> 00:55:43.240
[Amit Varma]: I'll make four or five observations about what you just spoke about. One, I'll express

00:55:43.240 --> 00:55:48.520
[Amit Varma]: a mild disagreement with your contention that America isn't all that bad when it comes to

00:55:48.520 --> 00:55:55.840
[Amit Varma]: special interests. Because I think that while there aren't mostly any overt abuses of power

00:55:55.840 --> 00:56:00.920
[Amit Varma]: like we see in India, I think at the level of public policy and economic policy, there

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:05.840
[Amit Varma]: is a lot of damage which is done, which kind of goes unseen. And to all my readers, I'd

00:56:05.840 --> 00:56:11.520
[Amit Varma]: recommend this book by Jonathan Rauch called Government's End. I'll link it from the show

00:56:11.520 --> 00:56:16.560
[Amit Varma]: notes and which was an eye opener for me in just understanding how much of the system

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:23.520
[Guest]: there is sort of ruled by a special interest. Let me briefly, I agree with you. If you take

00:56:23.520 --> 00:56:29.160
[Guest]: gun control issue or the healthcare to particularly glaring issues, you can see the power of the

00:56:29.160 --> 00:56:34.800
[Guest]: vested interests and the way the American Congress or the American system is responding.

00:56:34.800 --> 00:56:39.720
[Guest]: Having said that, there are two broad points. That's the reason why I said there's a distinction.

00:56:39.720 --> 00:56:44.280
[Guest]: There's no comparison between what we're doing and what they're doing to themselves. And

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:52.080
[Guest]: two, despite that, they use legal means to do foolish things like the healthcare system

00:56:52.080 --> 00:56:59.080
[Guest]: or gun control. They're doing legally, unwisely because of vested interests, et cetera, et

00:56:59.080 --> 00:57:04.280
[Guest]: cetera. It's not illegal things. And the moment you do something illegal, the system is strong

00:57:04.280 --> 00:57:09.960
[Guest]: enough to hold you to account pretty quickly and pretty efficiently. In that sense, certainly

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:15.520
[Guest]: for a country of that extraordinary civilizational strength and ideas and wealth, I don't for

00:57:15.520 --> 00:57:20.160
[Guest]: the life of me understand how they mess up healthcare so badly despite such expenditure,

00:57:20.160 --> 00:57:24.160
[Guest]: how almost every other day you keep hearing about mass shootings. It doesn't make any

00:57:24.160 --> 00:57:28.320
[Amit Varma]: sense to that extent. I completely agree with you. Yeah, I mean, I mean that distinction

00:57:28.320 --> 00:57:34.280
[Amit Varma]: about legality, I don't know what to make of that because it seems to me that when you

00:57:34.280 --> 00:57:40.480
[Amit Varma]: have given the state a monopoly on violence, and when as a people we have normalized the

00:57:40.480 --> 00:57:45.440
[Amit Varma]: massive levels of coercion that we face on a daily basis, it might then be said that

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:50.320
[Amit Varma]: a lot of things which are wrong can easily be legal and therefore your guiding principles

00:57:50.320 --> 00:57:54.960
[Amit Varma]: should be virtue rather than legality per se. But leaving that aside, I mean, that's

00:57:54.960 --> 00:58:00.360
[Amit Varma]: another distinction. You also mentioned the three points Ambedkar raises. So my second

00:58:00.360 --> 00:58:05.200
[Amit Varma]: observation is about the first of them. Ambedkar, of course, is one of the intellectuals I admired

00:58:05.200 --> 00:58:11.840
[Amit Varma]: most in the 20th century, just an absolutely remarkable man beyond the familiar dimensions

00:58:11.840 --> 00:58:16.920
[Amit Varma]: in which people talk about him. But you mentioned about how he implored Indian people to give

00:58:16.920 --> 00:58:22.040
[Amit Varma]: up the grammar of anarchy. And this observation of mine is an aside not really related to

00:58:22.040 --> 00:58:28.440
[Amit Varma]: the broader episode, but it strikes me that in that one instance, it seems very convenient

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:34.120
[Amit Varma]: to me where he says that, listen, we use the grammar of anarchy when protesting against

00:58:34.120 --> 00:58:40.640
[Amit Varma]: our oppressors. But you may not use the grammar of anarchy when protesting against your oppressors.

00:58:40.640 --> 00:58:45.240
[Guest]: I don't think it's a fair characterization. He's saying once you have the tools of vote

00:58:45.240 --> 00:58:50.480
[Guest]: and free speech, you no longer have the right to use violence or obstructionism. We had

00:58:50.480 --> 00:58:57.680
[Guest]: neither during the alien rule. I think that's the context. I completely am with Ambedkar

00:58:57.680 --> 00:58:58.680
[Amit Varma]: on that.

00:58:58.680 --> 00:59:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I mean, to be fair enough, the counter to that would be that people like Gokhale

00:59:03.120 --> 00:59:07.320
[Amit Varma]: and Ranade and you know, the the Indian liberals who were really, in a sense, British liberals

00:59:07.320 --> 00:59:13.440
[Amit Varma]: of the late 19th century, actually tried to work with the Empire in a constitutional way

00:59:13.440 --> 00:59:17.960
[Amit Varma]: with petitions and so on and so forth. So the British could have argued that, hey, we

00:59:17.960 --> 00:59:22.240
[Amit Varma]: have a process in place also, of course, they didn't have the vote and all of those things.

00:59:22.240 --> 00:59:25.840
[Amit Varma]: So that point of Ambedkar is well taken that we build a constitutional democracy.

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:29.880
[Guest]: And I might even go a little beyond that and say something extremely controversial. I'm

00:59:29.880 --> 00:59:34.280
[Guest]: sure I'm going to be attacked by many people. If we actually give ourselves a little bit

00:59:34.280 --> 00:59:41.200
[Guest]: more chance for that evolution, particularly from 1937. 37 was when we really had self

00:59:41.200 --> 00:59:48.480
[Guest]: governance in states with the Government of India Act of 1935. Two terrible things happened

00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:53.760
[Guest]: that did, I think, immense and lasting damage to our country's democratic evolution. The

00:59:53.760 --> 00:59:59.920
[Guest]: first was the Second World War. Mahatma Gandhi, because of political compulsions, in an act

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:05.920
[Guest]: of unwisdom, I dare say that he directed the Congress governments to resign. That's the

01:00:05.920 --> 01:00:10.840
[Guest]: day when Jinnah called it the day of deliverance. It was a political compulsion. I understand

01:00:10.840 --> 01:00:15.520
[Guest]: that. But I think it did immense damage to the country because the Congress governments

01:00:15.520 --> 01:00:20.320
[Guest]: were doing an extremely good job because they were men of honor, irrespective of the structural

01:00:20.320 --> 01:00:25.200
[Guest]: issues of the constitutional framework, they were actually doing trying to do the right

01:00:25.200 --> 01:00:29.760
[Guest]: things to make people understand the meaning of democracy. Local governments could have

01:00:29.760 --> 01:00:33.400
[Guest]: been institutionalized effectively. Many other things, you know, self-government, art of

01:00:33.400 --> 01:00:37.480
[Guest]: self-governance would have slowly learned, though there was limited franchise, etc. That

01:00:37.480 --> 01:00:42.440
[Guest]: was interrupted very rudely. And suddenly, without any further experience, we got one

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:46.560
[Guest]: day freedom, the flags changed, and we said we are a free country. We had no understanding

01:00:46.560 --> 01:00:54.200
[Guest]: or experience. The 1942 made things even worse. The moment you indulge in this grammar of

01:00:54.200 --> 01:00:58.520
[Guest]: anarchy, I don't know how moral it was in the first place. The Quit India Movement.

01:00:58.520 --> 01:01:04.920
[Guest]: And the whole world was fighting against an extraordinarily dangerous tyrant, an idealist

01:01:04.920 --> 01:01:13.080
[Guest]: idealist. He wanted to reshape the world in his vision. But a tremendous threat to humanity

01:01:13.080 --> 01:01:17.400
[Guest]: as we understood the moral values as we understood that is one broader moral issue. But as a

01:01:17.400 --> 01:01:22.760
[Guest]: practical issue, that perhaps made it even harder. So if we gave ourselves a little more

01:01:22.760 --> 01:01:28.040
[Guest]: of that evolutionary thing, and gave our people a chance to understand the self-governance

01:01:28.040 --> 01:01:33.040
[Guest]: and its limits and its possibilities, particularly the local governance and accountability, I

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:35.720
[Guest]: think our democratic transition would have been far better.

01:01:35.720 --> 01:01:42.640
[Amit Varma]: My third observation is a dual observation, really. It's one about the point you made

01:01:42.640 --> 01:01:46.840
[Amit Varma]: about how our great leaders, because they were great leaders, and they were sort of

01:01:46.840 --> 01:01:51.520
[Amit Varma]: assuming that future leaders will be like them, did not build the constitutional safeguards

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:56.640
[Amit Varma]: that they should have and that a healthy democracy needs. And my observation here would be that

01:01:56.640 --> 01:02:02.600
[Amit Varma]: again, as I postulated earlier, it's these leaders were great because of the incentives

01:02:02.600 --> 01:02:06.520
[Amit Varma]: that brought them to where they were, they were not animated by a lust for power, when

01:02:06.520 --> 01:02:10.520
[Amit Varma]: they joined the freedom movement, it was only out of idealism and wanting to do good for

01:02:10.520 --> 01:02:16.800
[Amit Varma]: people. And those are not the sort of drives that would, you know, take someone into politics

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:21.960
[Amit Varma]: today or help them succeed. And perhaps they got carried away by that. And like you correctly

01:02:21.960 --> 01:02:26.440
[Amit Varma]: said, assume that, you know, all we need is good leaders whom the people will duly elect

01:02:26.440 --> 01:02:31.640
[Amit Varma]: and all will be well and that's not the case. The second point you made about the urge to

01:02:31.640 --> 01:02:37.040
[Amit Varma]: decentralization and the centralization that we embedded in our constitution and our institutions.

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:42.400
[Amit Varma]: I did an interesting episode with the historian Gyan Prakash, who's written this very illuminating

01:02:42.400 --> 01:02:48.360
[Amit Varma]: book called Emergency Chronicles. And his central thesis there is that, look, Indira

01:02:48.360 --> 01:02:52.920
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi did not do anything illegal during the emergency. All the powers were powers

01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:59.080
[Amit Varma]: granted to her by the constitution, the over centralization and all that. And Gyan's theory

01:02:59.080 --> 01:03:03.680
[Amit Varma]: on that was that, look, at the time the framers of the constitution were sitting together

01:03:03.680 --> 01:03:09.360
[Amit Varma]: in their room in Delhi, the country was erupting in violence all over. You know, they did not

01:03:09.360 --> 01:03:13.840
[Amit Varma]: know that this country would stay together. They did not know like today with hindsight,

01:03:13.840 --> 01:03:18.760
[Amit Varma]: we know that yeah, you know, the center did hold, but they did not know that. And therefore

01:03:18.760 --> 01:03:26.160
[Amit Varma]: that urge to centralization is perhaps understandable, given the context and the contingency. And

01:03:26.160 --> 01:03:33.680
[Amit Varma]: this is just just an observation, not my question. My question really then comes down to the

01:03:33.680 --> 01:03:41.480
[Amit Varma]: whole issue of voter apathy. Like, why are we so apathetic? Why do we I mean, we vote

01:03:41.480 --> 01:03:46.080
[Amit Varma]: in large numbers, but we almost assume that our vote won't really make a difference. It

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:52.520
[Amit Varma]: is almost like, you know, one friend of mine once speculated that this vote is an expressive

01:03:52.520 --> 01:03:56.760
[Amit Varma]: vote, the same way that we go to watch our favorite football team and we cheer for them,

01:03:56.760 --> 01:04:02.560
[Amit Varma]: the vote is we are expressing our tribal affiliation, so to say. But we almost seem to have assumed

01:04:02.560 --> 01:04:08.780
[Amit Varma]: that our vote won't make a difference. And does this have something to do with the institutions

01:04:08.780 --> 01:04:12.880
[Amit Varma]: that are in place where there is such a disconnect between power and accountability, especially

01:04:12.880 --> 01:04:18.200
[Guest]: at the local level? Absolutely, absolutely. While you know, all our lives, you and I and

01:04:18.200 --> 01:04:22.840
[Guest]: many of many like us have been urging people to exercise the right to vote without which

01:04:22.840 --> 01:04:27.640
[Guest]: you cannot bring about change and civic duty, not only right, etc. It's absolutely true.

01:04:27.640 --> 01:04:31.680
[Guest]: That's the only way you can bring about change. As I keep telling people, the only antidote

01:04:31.680 --> 01:04:36.720
[Guest]: to the ills of a democracy is more democracy and better democracy, not sitting out, not

01:04:36.720 --> 01:04:43.880
[Guest]: rejecting it is absurd. Having said that, the people at large are not entirely wrong

01:04:43.880 --> 01:04:48.360
[Guest]: in coming to the sad conclusion that their vote does not seem to make a difference because

01:04:48.360 --> 01:04:54.280
[Guest]: of centralization. Again, let me give a concrete example. Delhi, whether you subscribe to one

01:04:54.280 --> 01:04:59.400
[Guest]: party or another, that's not material now. We're talking larger context. There are some

01:04:59.400 --> 01:05:06.360
[Guest]: some signs of hope, some shoots. Why? Because the citizen of Delhi understood intuitively

01:05:06.360 --> 01:05:12.520
[Guest]: that a vote in Delhi makes a difference to Delhi to at least some extent, real difference.

01:05:12.520 --> 01:05:16.480
[Guest]: It may not make all the difference like rule of law. Other big things will not be changed.

01:05:16.480 --> 01:05:21.720
[Guest]: But your local education, health care, basic service delivery, corruption free services,

01:05:21.720 --> 01:05:28.400
[Guest]: other things are possible because Delhi has a situation where the chief executive of Delhi

01:05:28.400 --> 01:05:34.040
[Guest]: is the most empowered mayor of India, much less empowered than any mayor anywhere in

01:05:34.040 --> 01:05:38.680
[Guest]: the world. But because we don't have the strength of local governments by Indian standards,

01:05:38.680 --> 01:05:42.880
[Guest]: chief minister of Delhi is the most empowered mayor of India. Therefore, some kind of a

01:05:42.880 --> 01:05:47.160
[Guest]: change is possible. Mumbai, the same thing is not there. Mumbai actually is much more

01:05:47.160 --> 01:05:51.480
[Guest]: vibrant as a city in my view. I hope it remains to be so, but I've known Mumbai for quite

01:05:51.480 --> 01:05:58.440
[Guest]: some time. I love that city, the kind of citizen activism, the spirit of the community, the

01:05:58.440 --> 01:06:06.640
[Guest]: voluntary sector, the civil society, and the general performance and trust from punctuality

01:06:06.640 --> 01:06:13.400
[Guest]: to delivery. And yet, a voter in Mumbai does not feel that her vote makes a difference.

01:06:13.400 --> 01:06:18.240
[Guest]: Because unless you change the whole of Maharashtra, you cannot change Mumbai. And given India's

01:06:18.240 --> 01:06:23.840
[Guest]: complexity, it's much harder to make rural India recognize its own value of its own vote

01:06:23.840 --> 01:06:29.040
[Guest]: and make it as a powerful tool to change. So that certainly if some people come to this

01:06:29.040 --> 01:06:33.920
[Guest]: sad conclusion, I can understand. I don't accept that. I would urge them to still fight

01:06:33.920 --> 01:06:41.520
[Guest]: that despair and then figure out the way changes will happen. Let me give another example.

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:47.280
[Guest]: What did Korean do? We are looking at democracy or institutions only as the union government,

01:06:47.280 --> 01:06:52.120
[Guest]: state government, etc. But what did Korean do? The moment the incentives are properly

01:06:52.120 --> 01:06:58.640
[Guest]: aligned, there is not a single cooperative society's member who does not believe that

01:06:58.640 --> 01:07:04.240
[Guest]: his or her vote does not matter, his vote does not matter. They know their vote matters.

01:07:04.240 --> 01:07:09.920
[Guest]: There's the same people of India, castridden, superstitious, poor, often illiterate and

01:07:09.920 --> 01:07:17.120
[Guest]: all those things. And yet, the self interest is clearly manifest. I keep telling people

01:07:17.120 --> 01:07:24.320
[Guest]: about the apartment complex where I live. After this, this recording, I go home and

01:07:24.320 --> 01:07:30.320
[Guest]: suppose the elevator is not functioning. My elderly mother 84 years old, she is with me,

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:34.160
[Guest]: and she obviously cannot climb stairs because of arthritic and other problems. I'm not going

01:07:34.160 --> 01:07:39.240
[Guest]: to keep quiet, I'll holler. Whoever is managing, I've chosen, we've all chosen. We're paying

01:07:39.240 --> 01:07:44.800
[Guest]: monthly maintenance. I'm not going to keep quiet because my vote matters. Matters in

01:07:44.800 --> 01:07:49.760
[Guest]: a way that I directly understand, not some romantic way of Bharat Mata. The elevator

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:55.280
[Guest]: is not functioning. The electricity outages are there. The parking is bad. Watch and what

01:07:55.280 --> 01:07:58.360
[Guest]: is inadequate, water supply is interrupted. These things matter.

01:07:58.360 --> 01:08:01.760
[Guest]: And these are simple things which everyone gets and experiences.

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:05.960
[Guest]: That's what I mean. When I said democracy is not about the noble and romantic things,

01:08:05.960 --> 01:08:10.520
[Guest]: it's about simple and practical things which are collectively needed. And unless you bring

01:08:10.520 --> 01:08:15.920
[Guest]: that connect, a vote does not become a very meaningful tool. That's what I mean. So the

01:08:15.920 --> 01:08:23.280
[Guest]: answer is for heaven's sake, let people make decisions as long as their decisions don't

01:08:23.280 --> 01:08:29.400
[Guest]: impact other people. If you decide in Mumbai or a part of Mumbai in Juhu, something, if

01:08:29.400 --> 01:08:32.920
[Guest]: that decision is bad, as long as I'm not affected by the decision, I think you should have that

01:08:32.920 --> 01:08:36.800
[Guest]: freedom to commit mistakes and learn from that. And we can certainly sit there and advise

01:08:36.800 --> 01:08:41.200
[Guest]: them or you can hold them to account if something goes terribly wrong, but you cannot deny them

01:08:41.200 --> 01:08:47.160
[Guest]: the decision making power because, and this again, a very controversial one that I'm saying,

01:08:47.160 --> 01:08:56.120
[Guest]: I truly believe and I say it often that even a villain locally controlling the issues,

01:08:56.120 --> 01:09:00.880
[Guest]: a local leader who is a villain is better than an angel who is a distant person.

01:09:00.880 --> 01:09:05.360
[Guest]: The notion that you require some extraordinary people, Mahatma Gandhi like figures to govern

01:09:05.360 --> 01:09:10.000
[Guest]: the destinies of a nation, somehow things will be okay, is a dangerous delusion.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:16.200
[Amit Varma]: That's a very profound insight. And it's something that I often keep hopping on repeatedly is

01:09:16.200 --> 01:09:22.560
[Amit Varma]: that you should have rules and institutions in place. So that even if the worst, most

01:09:22.560 --> 01:09:27.600
[Amit Varma]: evil power hungry human being you can think of is in charge, he can't do much damage because

01:09:27.600 --> 01:09:32.400
[Amit Varma]: there are enough checks and balances. And what you've said ties into that, that a local

01:09:32.400 --> 01:09:36.720
[Amit Varma]: leader who is accountable immediately to his people and depends on them for his power will

01:09:36.720 --> 01:09:41.120
[Amit Varma]: have to deliver, he might be evil, it doesn't matter, he has to get the job done. And you

01:09:41.120 --> 01:09:44.880
[Amit Varma]: know, I did an old episode with Shruti Rajagopalan, which I'll again link from the show notes

01:09:44.880 --> 01:09:50.600
[Amit Varma]: on urban governance. And what she laid out with great clarity in that was that, you know,

01:09:50.600 --> 01:09:54.840
[Amit Varma]: taking Mumbai as an example, is that there is a disconnect between power and accountability,

01:09:54.840 --> 01:09:59.440
[Amit Varma]: which is fatal in a democracy. The people you vote for your local corporators and councillors

01:09:59.440 --> 01:10:04.840
[Amit Varma]: and so on don't really have much power to get much done. And the people who do have

01:10:04.840 --> 01:10:10.640
[Amit Varma]: power, which is at the state level are not reliant on the urban vote, they are catering

01:10:10.640 --> 01:10:15.240
[Amit Varma]: more to the rural vote banks. And therefore, who's looking after your interests. And this

01:10:15.240 --> 01:10:19.480
[Amit Varma]: is something that I know, you know, the subject of federalism, government being as local as

01:10:19.480 --> 01:10:24.520
[Amit Varma]: possible, I know is something that has been very close to your heart as well. And you

01:10:24.520 --> 01:10:29.760
[Amit Varma]: know, you fought for it. And it strikes me and again, my lament and hopefully it's naive

01:10:29.760 --> 01:10:36.400
[Amit Varma]: and too pessimistic, and things are not so bad. But my lament is that, look, the only

01:10:36.400 --> 01:10:41.600
[Amit Varma]: people who can change this are the people who are incentivized against changing it,

01:10:41.600 --> 01:10:45.600
[Amit Varma]: because obviously, they want to consolidate their own power. So why would you devolve

01:10:45.600 --> 01:10:47.600
[Guest]: power away from yourself?

01:10:47.600 --> 01:10:54.120
[Guest]: It's an extremely challenging question. You're totally right. I worked very hard at one stage,

01:10:54.120 --> 01:11:00.440
[Guest]: became this close to getting the constitution amended 73rd, 74th amendments, those provisions,

01:11:00.440 --> 01:11:04.120
[Guest]: in order to really make it a meaningful thing. And there was political executive was ready

01:11:04.120 --> 01:11:09.500
[Guest]: and willing. And the political parties were ready and willing. But because of the fall

01:11:09.500 --> 01:11:13.800
[Guest]: is not one. One other thing I realized in life is it's not always the evil man who stops

01:11:13.800 --> 01:11:21.440
[Guest]: good things. Oftentimes, it's the unwise good man, who is actually a bigger enemy. Unwisdom

01:11:21.440 --> 01:11:27.280
[Guest]: is greater challenge than dishonesty. I know it's not a fashionable thing to say, but in

01:11:27.280 --> 01:11:33.240
[Guest]: my life time and again, I saw, uh, I know how to deal with a crook. Relatively speaking,

01:11:33.240 --> 01:11:38.480
[Guest]: I don't know how to deal with an unwise person, particularly when he has this virtue of honesty.

01:11:38.480 --> 01:11:45.720
[Guest]: Uh, so that didn't happen, but there are some levers. For instance, uh, the union is transferring

01:11:45.720 --> 01:11:51.400
[Guest]: significant amount of resources to States. If you take all put together now, latest newspaper

01:11:51.400 --> 01:11:56.560
[Guest]: accounts say that Delhi is trying to bring down the, the share of the States that we

01:11:56.560 --> 01:12:02.480
[Guest]: will have to see the 15th finance commission, et cetera. But, um, something like 47.5% of

01:12:02.480 --> 01:12:07.520
[Guest]: the total union budget is transferred to States, uh, either constitutional devolution or other

01:12:07.520 --> 01:12:15.200
[Guest]: forms of transfer. Supposing some significant portion of it directly goes to the local garments

01:12:15.200 --> 01:12:19.520
[Guest]: on a per capita basis. You're not increasing the cake. You are just interstate. You're

01:12:19.520 --> 01:12:23.720
[Guest]: changing it. And to that extent, you will force the States to do all some of the responsibilities

01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:27.440
[Guest]: like, you know, paying the salaries of teachers and schools. It's not that they seem to get

01:12:27.440 --> 01:12:31.680
[Guest]: the money. They simply have to pay from their hands, but they also control the way the school

01:12:31.680 --> 01:12:38.280
[Guest]: is managed or local health center, for instance. Uh, that's one easy way of empowering because

01:12:38.280 --> 01:12:42.920
[Guest]: power follows money. The constitutionally we created a monster structure, the 73rd,

01:12:42.920 --> 01:12:47.560
[Guest]: 74th amendments in the constitution are very well-meaning, but extremely unwise. They created

01:12:47.560 --> 01:12:52.880
[Guest]: an over-structured underpowered local government system. So if the political consensus is there

01:12:52.880 --> 01:12:57.680
[Guest]: to change that, it's wonderful. I would welcome it. As I said, I tried very hard at one stage,

01:12:57.680 --> 01:13:03.440
[Guest]: but at the last moment we failed, but this is one way. Uh, the second way is in telling

01:13:03.440 --> 01:13:07.920
[Guest]: on a recently an effort was made, at least urban local comments. No, in urban areas,

01:13:07.920 --> 01:13:12.600
[Guest]: people are increasingly aware of their, their power and their deprivation. Both we are paying

01:13:12.600 --> 01:13:16.920
[Guest]: taxes. We are sustaining ourselves to say state is not funding us. And yet even the

01:13:16.920 --> 01:13:21.280
[Guest]: most basic services we're not getting that anger is there and urban areas, their problem

01:13:21.280 --> 01:13:25.560
[Guest]: solvers. After all the best of India and urban areas, that's where money, that's where economy,

01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:30.640
[Guest]: that's where talent is. Uh, this voice is heard. And if it's made politically an influential

01:13:30.640 --> 01:13:35.640
[Guest]: voice, at least our cities and urban areas, perhaps you can have a beginning what's happening

01:13:35.640 --> 01:13:40.000
[Guest]: in Delhi could happen elsewhere slowly. And therefore that also will politically transform

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:45.080
[Guest]: the country, not only in terms of governance and outcomes. So I think there are some possibilities

01:13:45.080 --> 01:13:50.240
[Guest]: if our leaders are wise, I'm not saying empower blindly, hold them, take on very strongly,

01:13:50.240 --> 01:13:57.840
[Guest]: have a strong independent ombudsman system. You control that and be ruthless. Though theoretically,

01:13:57.840 --> 01:14:00.720
[Guest]: I mean, when you are doing all ugly things and there's no control, why should you bother

01:14:00.720 --> 01:14:05.840
[Guest]: about them? But I wouldn't like to use that argument. My idea or anybody's idea of decentralization

01:14:05.840 --> 01:14:10.620
[Guest]: is not decentralized corruption or abuse of power. It is to actually improve things. Therefore,

01:14:10.620 --> 01:14:14.600
[Guest]: you have all the safeguards. I have no quarrel at all. As long as they are institutionally

01:14:14.600 --> 01:14:19.600
[Guest]: independent of the political part of the government look like the local framework or something

01:14:19.600 --> 01:14:26.200
[Guest]: else. So there are levers. It's hard because the constitutional injunctions are very, very

01:14:26.200 --> 01:14:32.720
[Guest]: rigid and unwise. Change it. If you can take, for instance, German constitution in about

01:14:32.720 --> 01:14:40.080
[Guest]: 53 words, very elegantly, the German constitution clearly outlines the independence and autonomy

01:14:40.080 --> 01:14:44.880
[Guest]: of the local governments and the accountability and then leaves the rest of it to the local

01:14:44.880 --> 01:14:50.800
[Guest]: statutes, the state of statutes. India is the only country in the world, the only country

01:14:50.800 --> 01:14:55.480
[Guest]: in the world where the local government structure is elaborately prescribed in the constitution

01:14:55.480 --> 01:15:01.080
[Guest]: of the federal government. It's absurd. It's so absurd that we're not able to even recognize

01:15:01.080 --> 01:15:07.120
[Guest]: because we think it's normal. It's abnormal. In our medical textbooks, a textbook of pathology,

01:15:07.120 --> 01:15:11.840
[Guest]: there was a great author called Boyd, very poetic. You know, the red blood cells of the

01:15:11.840 --> 01:15:18.640
