[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen. I'm chatting with J.P. Narayan about the state

01:18:32.760 --> 01:18:38.280
[Amit Varma]: of Indian politics and his own personal journey in politics. And, you know, we've kind of

01:18:38.280 --> 01:18:43.080
[Amit Varma]: so far spent time talking about Indian politics in general, the nature of politics in general

01:18:43.080 --> 01:18:47.960
[Amit Varma]: and a little bit of a personal journey. I want to now dovetail into your actual joining

01:18:47.960 --> 01:18:53.560
[Amit Varma]: politics. Like, is that decision to leave the IAS and join politics something you mulled

01:18:53.560 --> 01:18:57.600
[Amit Varma]: over a period of time? Or, you know, how was the process? What drove it?

01:18:57.600 --> 01:19:03.820
[Guest]: I never thought of joining politics. I left IAS to build a movement. So politics came

01:19:03.820 --> 01:19:10.040
[Guest]: more than 10 years later. 96, I left IAS, built looks at the movement and foundation

01:19:10.040 --> 01:19:16.600
[Guest]: for democratic reforms. And then I was lucky to be involved in quite a few significant

01:19:16.600 --> 01:19:23.160
[Guest]: changes in terms of governance reform, several constitutional amendments, several changes

01:19:23.160 --> 01:19:28.280
[Guest]: in law and so on and so forth. At a certain stage, about 10 years after this, by the time

01:19:28.280 --> 01:19:32.560
[Guest]: we became perhaps one of the more influential and one of the more respected movements in

01:19:32.560 --> 01:19:37.720
[Guest]: the country in terms of governance reform, only because the field is very scarce now.

01:19:37.720 --> 01:19:47.680
[Guest]: There are not many people. Again, as I said, the bar is very low. But then at one stage,

01:19:47.680 --> 01:19:53.200
[Guest]: two things happen, at least two ideas. One is, perhaps with a certain amount of economic

01:19:53.200 --> 01:20:02.320
[Guest]: reform and creeping prosperity, and media and internet and communications, perhaps a

01:20:02.320 --> 01:20:08.440
[Guest]: significant section of the population, let's say about 10%, that was my assumption, 10%.

01:20:08.440 --> 01:20:16.600
[Guest]: I'm now more and more aware of what is at stake, and they're willing to vote. According

01:20:16.600 --> 01:20:22.720
[Guest]: to what they believe is right and looking into the future, rather than voting for who

01:20:22.720 --> 01:20:27.200
[Guest]: will win in an electoral system, which always rewards the winner, and there are no second

01:20:27.200 --> 01:20:34.720
[Guest]: prizes winner-take-all system. I sensed, or I felt, I assessed, wrongly as it turned out,

01:20:34.720 --> 01:20:39.560
[Guest]: that 10% people in India are perhaps ready to vote for change, real change, on a sustained

01:20:39.560 --> 01:20:44.960
[Guest]: basis. I was certain if 10% people are willing to vote for that on a sustained basis, the

01:20:44.960 --> 01:20:49.000
[Guest]: political system will respond immediately. Whatever you say about our politicians and

01:20:49.000 --> 01:20:54.120
[Guest]: political parties, they understand this, the way things are happening, electoral patterns,

01:20:54.120 --> 01:20:58.280
[Guest]: and immediately they'll embrace the ideas. Real change does not happen because you with

01:20:58.280 --> 01:21:03.160
[Guest]: one fell swoop destroyed the existing system. It happens because the political parties change

01:21:03.160 --> 01:21:07.560
[Guest]: their behavior and their ideas to reflect the people's aspirations in order to get the

01:21:07.560 --> 01:21:13.960
[Guest]: vote, and that's a perfectly legitimate incentive. So I felt if 10% is there for transformation

01:21:13.960 --> 01:21:20.520
[Guest]: of our politics and governance, then the parties will respond. That was my expectation.

01:21:20.520 --> 01:21:26.120
[Guest]: The second is, I also sensed that while some significant changes we could engineer, like

01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:30.880
[Guest]: the electoral funding law of 2003 after the Halka scam, India has actually a pretty good

01:21:30.880 --> 01:21:34.480
[Guest]: funding law. Most people don't realize it, but that simply is not enough because most

01:21:34.480 --> 01:21:38.320
[Guest]: of our problem is not legitimate funding for campaigning. It is illegitimate funding for

01:21:38.320 --> 01:21:43.360
[Guest]: wood-buying and many other dirty things. Similarly, the Right to Information Act, along with Erna

01:21:43.360 --> 01:21:47.600
[Guest]: Roy, was instrumental in drafting that law, and the government of the day was willing

01:21:47.600 --> 01:21:50.440
[Guest]: to do it, and therefore something would happen, and all the political parties were willing

01:21:50.440 --> 01:21:56.360
[Guest]: to do it. The 91st Amendment, 97th Amendment, Cooperative Autonomy, 99th Amendment, the

01:21:56.360 --> 01:22:00.760
[Guest]: National Judicial Commission, which the Supreme Court unwisely quashed it subsequently, the

01:22:00.760 --> 01:22:05.000
[Guest]: local court's law, and several things we could engineer.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:10.560
[Guest]: But when it came to the fundamental change required in the governance process, decentralization,

01:22:10.560 --> 01:22:14.760
[Guest]: and I mentioned to you, for instance, how the hurdles ultimately blocked it, or electoral

01:22:14.760 --> 01:22:20.200
[Guest]: system change, or rule of law change, the big changes, I felt that the political system

01:22:20.200 --> 01:22:27.280
[Guest]: will not listen unless there are electoral consequences. As I said rightly, if it's going

01:22:27.280 --> 01:22:31.600
[Guest]: to hurt them politically, why should they do it? What is the incentive? Other good things,

01:22:31.600 --> 01:22:34.480
[Guest]: well, you may get some goodwill, and you may want to do some good things. As long as it

01:22:34.480 --> 01:22:40.120
[Guest]: doesn't hurt you, you may want to do it. So, I felt if 10% people are willing to vote

01:22:40.120 --> 01:22:45.000
[Guest]: for that, they realize it's actually hurtful to them if they don't come onto the bandwagon.

01:22:45.000 --> 01:22:53.760
[Guest]: You see, these two things, which made us think that maybe we should look at a political platform

01:22:53.760 --> 01:22:58.800
[Guest]: of the way it should be, the way it is not in India. So, after a very agonizing period,

01:22:58.800 --> 01:23:04.200
[Guest]: because intuitively, I am not for partisan politics, I'm not suitable for that. My whole

01:23:04.200 --> 01:23:09.000
[Guest]: approach, my life, my work, everybody knows about that, and even my articulation, not

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:13.520
[Guest]: about consensus building, how to reconcile rather than how to differentiate. Whereas

01:23:13.520 --> 01:23:18.680
[Guest]: politics is about how to segment the market and take your share. And therefore, that hard

01:23:18.680 --> 01:23:24.960
[Guest]: edge, that pretends of huge differences, making everything black and white. That is the nature

01:23:24.960 --> 01:23:31.000
[Guest]: of politics world over. So, it is that that compelled us to join, to form a political

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:37.560
[Guest]: party. As it turned out, in urban India, particularly big cities, the 10% assessment was right.

01:23:37.560 --> 01:23:43.320
[Guest]: In rural India, I think it's never beyond about a couple of percentage points. And my

01:23:43.320 --> 01:23:48.880
[Guest]: assessment is that in the absence of local governments in urban India, if urban India

01:23:48.880 --> 01:23:54.040
[Guest]: local governments are allowed this 10% would have become 30%. Or even a governing thing,

01:23:54.040 --> 01:24:00.320
[Guest]: at least citizens get more involved in the field. See people once they shed the skepticism,

01:24:00.320 --> 01:24:06.840
[Guest]: for instance, you know, when Lalu Yadav was holding sway for about 15 years in Bihar,

01:24:06.840 --> 01:24:11.400
[Guest]: in one election, if you recall, Nitish Kumar got a significant vote, but not a maturity.

01:24:11.400 --> 01:24:16.280
[Guest]: Once people realize that yes, we're actually much more numerically stronger than what we

01:24:16.280 --> 01:24:21.560
[Guest]: thought. Next time when the chance came, they voted him to power very comfortably. Similar

01:24:21.560 --> 01:24:25.640
[Guest]: thing in Delhi, if you recall, initially, they gave a significant percentage, but not

01:24:25.640 --> 01:24:30.160
[Guest]: a winning margin. Once they realize that next time around, they go. So that's the way electoral

01:24:30.160 --> 01:24:34.640
[Guest]: politics in the first past the post system they operate. Therefore, in big cities, if

01:24:34.640 --> 01:24:39.120
[Guest]: you have self governing models, like in Delhi, that kind of a thing doesn't matter what name

01:24:39.120 --> 01:24:43.400
[Guest]: of the platform, but basically, if it's an ethical and credible thing with a clear sense

01:24:43.400 --> 01:24:47.880
[Guest]: of where we should go, people will respond. But rural India is nowhere near that because

01:24:47.880 --> 01:24:54.800
[Guest]: there is this clientelism. If you recall, I mentioned something about the basic delivery

01:24:54.800 --> 01:25:00.880
[Guest]: of services lacking in this country. Therefore, the ordinary people, they're desperate to

01:25:00.880 --> 01:25:06.400
[Guest]: hold on to the coattails of somebody in politics, the local political workers, a machine. So

01:25:06.400 --> 01:25:09.880
[Guest]: it's not merely wood buying that, of course, important. It's not really free base. It's

01:25:09.880 --> 01:25:14.160
[Guest]: also that without them, you have no sense of survival, not that they are doing anything

01:25:14.160 --> 01:25:19.880
[Guest]: very great, but at least they're giving you some access. And you cannot build an ethical

01:25:19.880 --> 01:25:26.120
[Guest]: party with such a vast machine of thousands of workers five years around the year working.

01:25:26.120 --> 01:25:30.000
[Guest]: It's not possible. Freedom struggle is possible. So they have to be necessarily mercenary in

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:35.520
[Guest]: some form or the other. Either somebody pays them or somebody allows them to make money

01:25:35.520 --> 01:25:39.840
[Guest]: by misoperating the system, the police cases, the contracts and tenders, the land grab,

01:25:39.840 --> 01:25:45.400
[Guest]: the ration shops, the transfers and postings of officials, petty contracts. This is the

01:25:45.400 --> 01:25:50.840
[Guest]: way it operates, the whole system. That's why it's so hard to substitute an established

01:25:50.840 --> 01:25:57.080
[Guest]: political party anywhere in the country. So because of this special problem in rural India,

01:25:57.080 --> 01:26:04.680
[Guest]: we underestimated the magnitude of the challenge. And once we felt that this vote is not enough,

01:26:04.680 --> 01:26:10.400
[Guest]: there's no path to reform, we decided that we will not invest our energy and time in

01:26:10.400 --> 01:26:16.440
[Guest]: this. We'll work in a different way. But I think one day or the other, India must move

01:26:16.440 --> 01:26:21.720
[Guest]: towards these political formations of a different kind or the major parties change in their

01:26:21.720 --> 01:26:25.360
[Guest]: way and therefore giving space for these kind of people and these kinds of ideas. That's

01:26:25.360 --> 01:26:29.080
[Guest]: the only way forward. You can't have a bloody revolution in the country. I don't believe

01:26:29.080 --> 01:26:33.680
[Guest]: a million people marching in Delhi or Hyderabad or Mumbai will change the country. It may

01:26:33.680 --> 01:26:37.640
[Guest]: become actually a grammar of anarchy. There are very few instances in human history where

01:26:37.640 --> 01:26:41.520
[Guest]: a million people sitting actually change things for the better.

