[Amit Varma]: So I have three observations slash questions here. Would it be fair to then characterize

01:26:47.960 --> 01:26:52.520
[Amit Varma]: our political system in the absence of the rule of law, which as you correctly pointed

01:26:52.520 --> 01:26:56.200
[Amit Varma]: out earlier, in most of the country, for most of the people, we don't have the rule of law

01:26:56.200 --> 01:27:01.720
[Amit Varma]: in the absence of the rule of law. Are our political parties basically different mafias

01:27:01.720 --> 01:27:07.600
[Amit Varma]: competing for the monopoly of violence that we give the state with its attendant consequences?

01:27:07.600 --> 01:27:14.080
[Guest]: Mafias may be a strong word, very pejorative word, but certainly they're feudal fiefdoms.

01:27:14.080 --> 01:27:19.120
[Guest]: They're personal jagirs. There's no doubt about it whatsoever. And my second observation

01:27:19.120 --> 01:27:25.360
[Amit Varma]: is actually what you said about as politics gets more local voters will be more incentivized

01:27:25.360 --> 01:27:29.800
[Amit Varma]: to, you know, to feel that they have a stake in the system. Extremely insightful, because

01:27:29.800 --> 01:27:34.560
[Amit Varma]: like in public choice theory, there is this phrase rational ignorance, where voters tend

01:27:34.560 --> 01:27:39.240
[Amit Varma]: to be apathetic, because every voter knows that at an individual level, his one vote

01:27:39.240 --> 01:27:44.840
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter. And therefore, when the reward is so low, why put in the hard work of educating

01:27:44.840 --> 01:27:49.000
[Amit Varma]: yourself on what is at stake and understanding public policy and economics and is rational

01:27:49.000 --> 01:27:54.320
[Amit Varma]: to be ignorant. But as you've just pointed out, that the more you increase the possibility

01:27:54.320 --> 01:27:59.520
[Amit Varma]: of that vote actually mattering, which it will at a local level, more the incentive

01:27:59.520 --> 01:28:05.120
[Amit Varma]: for him to be an informed citizen and actually take part in the democratic processes of the

01:28:05.120 --> 01:28:06.120
[Guest]: country.

01:28:06.120 --> 01:28:11.680
[Guest]: Absolutely. See, decentralization, obviously, you'll understand the consequences and a different

01:28:11.680 --> 01:28:18.280
[Guest]: electoral system where everyone actually counts. And therefore, even if you are 10% or 15%,

01:28:18.280 --> 01:28:23.520
[Guest]: that has a voice. And therefore, you know, if it is wasted, and you are Greens party

01:28:23.520 --> 01:28:29.360
[Guest]: 30 years ago, where were they? One, 2% take Germany, for instance. But over time, as more

01:28:29.360 --> 01:28:33.600
[Guest]: and more people were converted, right, wrong, I'm not going to ideologies and the philosophy,

01:28:33.600 --> 01:28:38.560
[Guest]: it became a significant party. So that space, we're not giving ourselves in this country.

01:28:38.560 --> 01:28:45.040
[Guest]: It's almost impossible to be outside the mainstream parties and be politically significant. Therefore,

01:28:45.040 --> 01:28:48.320
[Guest]: we have to really look at alternate electoral system and tremendous decentralization of

01:28:48.320 --> 01:28:52.680
[Guest]: power with accountability. Otherwise, this will be a very long and painful transition

01:28:52.680 --> 01:28:57.720
[Guest]: with enormous cost to society, unquestionably within the country. And in terms of global

01:28:57.720 --> 01:29:03.200
[Guest]: comparison, we will lose, we already lost dramatically, we will lose a lot, lot, lot

01:29:03.200 --> 01:29:04.200
[Guest]: more.

01:29:04.200 --> 01:29:08.840
[Amit Varma]: To come back to your journey in politics, you know, when I think of the political marketplace,

01:29:08.840 --> 01:29:14.800
[Amit Varma]: I've always sort of held the view that it is naive to expect change at the supply end,

01:29:14.800 --> 01:29:19.920
[Amit Varma]: you have to first the demand for change has to come from the demand end. And therefore,

01:29:19.920 --> 01:29:25.320
[Amit Varma]: it is more if you want to change politics, you can only change it via the culture, like

01:29:25.320 --> 01:29:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Andrew Breitbart once said, politics is downstream of culture. And to me, that sounds like a

01:29:29.880 --> 01:29:34.800
[Amit Varma]: very profound truth. And it seems to me that you know, when you leave the IAS, you decide

01:29:34.800 --> 01:29:38.720
[Amit Varma]: to start this movement. That's what you're trying to do. You're trying to influence the

01:29:38.720 --> 01:29:43.680
[Amit Varma]: demand and you're trying to influence change the culture. So that more than the 10% of

01:29:43.680 --> 01:29:49.360
[Amit Varma]: urban voters and the 2% of rural voters actually start fighting for good governance. But then

01:29:49.360 --> 01:29:52.840
[Amit Varma]: at some point, you decide that this is not enough, and you actually enter the supply

01:29:52.840 --> 01:29:58.120
[Amit Varma]: end yourself. So what prompted that change in that shift, so to say,

01:29:58.120 --> 01:30:04.800
[Guest]: No, as I said, these two estimates one, an optimistic one, that no, maybe an opportunity

01:30:04.800 --> 01:30:11.340
[Guest]: is now growing because of the economic growth a little bit and greater awareness and communications.

01:30:11.340 --> 01:30:15.200
[Guest]: The other, a little bit of anger against the political system, which is not willing to

01:30:15.200 --> 01:30:22.680
[Guest]: look at bigger changes. I think the combination of these two, probably one or two specifics

01:30:22.680 --> 01:30:28.640
[Guest]: also might have contributed to that at a particular point of time. For instance, we were very

01:30:28.640 --> 01:30:34.380
[Guest]: close to altering the electoral system. And the way I sell these changes to the political

01:30:34.380 --> 01:30:41.200
[Guest]: parties and major leaders is not the country's good, because I don't think they really motivated

01:30:41.200 --> 01:30:45.280
[Guest]: by that alone. I'm not saying they don't want it. I don't think that is enough motivation

01:30:45.280 --> 01:30:50.940
[Guest]: for them. It is their own political future and survival that matters. So at the time,

01:30:50.940 --> 01:30:56.560
[Guest]: the way I did was we did enormous research. We found that take the six largest states

01:30:56.560 --> 01:31:04.800
[Guest]: of India, UP, Bihar, Maharashtra, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, and Bengal, which account for 55%

01:31:04.800 --> 01:31:09.760
[Guest]: of the looks of our seats. At that time, things have changed because BJP has expanded his

01:31:09.760 --> 01:31:14.600
[Guest]: footprint in some of these states, which is actually against the trend. But at that time,

01:31:14.600 --> 01:31:22.600
[Guest]: 10 years ago, in four and a half states, Congress and BJP were irrelevant. In one and a half

01:31:22.600 --> 01:31:27.920
[Guest]: states, one state, Andhra Pradesh, where Congress was one of the dominant players, and Maharashtra,

01:31:27.920 --> 01:31:32.240
[Guest]: where BJP was a significant player, not yet a dominant player. Today it became a dominant

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:38.120
[Guest]: player. They have space. And similarly, Congress in alliance with the NCP was a significant

01:31:38.120 --> 01:31:43.160
[Guest]: player. Today it appears alliances have changed and nobody knows what happens. So we explained

01:31:43.160 --> 01:31:49.160
[Guest]: to both the Congress and BJP why this happened. In a first-past-the-post system, once your

01:31:49.160 --> 01:31:53.760
[Guest]: vote share comes below a certain threshold, people intuitively realize that a vote for

01:31:53.760 --> 01:31:59.360
[Guest]: you does not mean the seats. And therefore, immediately the idea of wasted vote kicks

01:31:59.360 --> 01:32:04.600
[Guest]: in. And therefore, very soon, that 25% vote becomes 5% vote. And therefore, the national

01:32:04.600 --> 01:32:12.000
[Guest]: parties actually gain in a system where there's nothing like a wasted vote. Provided you have

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:16.720
[Guest]: some safeguards to ensure that there's not too much of fragmentation, caste-based parties,

01:32:16.720 --> 01:32:21.000
[Guest]: there are ways of doing it. Reasonable threshold, rewarding the big party with extra seats and

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:25.160
[Guest]: all kinds of things. But incentives are dramatically altered. The reason why I am interested in

01:32:25.160 --> 01:32:32.960
[Guest]: that is once a candidate has no incentive to buy the votes, and if I spend money, Amit

01:32:32.960 --> 01:32:37.080
[Guest]: and many others along with me in the list will benefit, the incentive is no longer for

01:32:37.080 --> 01:32:41.480
[Guest]: me to buy. Why should I spend my 20 crores in order to benefit Amit? Life doesn't work

01:32:41.480 --> 01:32:46.920
[Guest]: that way. And the parties also, right now, they see a tremendous advantage in bringing

01:32:46.920 --> 01:32:52.960
[Guest]: money back without any ability to govern or desire to govern well, because they are winnable.

01:32:52.960 --> 01:32:57.320
[Guest]: Whereas tomorrow, it's the credibility of the person and overall respect that the panel

01:32:57.320 --> 01:33:01.320
[Guest]: enjoys, the slate of candidates, that will give you the voting. Therefore, the way the

01:33:01.320 --> 01:33:05.600
[Guest]: party thinks, the way the candidate thinks, these two will dramatically change. The way

01:33:05.600 --> 01:33:09.880
[Guest]: the people think that, no, if I vote for Amit because of moral considerations, that vote

01:33:09.880 --> 01:33:15.240
[Guest]: is wasted. And there's also most democratic voting in our system is tactical voting. Right.

01:33:15.240 --> 01:33:21.800
[Guest]: I don't vote for the best candidate. I vote for the second worst candidate. Exactly. Because

01:33:21.800 --> 01:33:26.080
[Guest]: my fear is if I vote for the right person, the very wrong person may actually come into

01:33:26.080 --> 01:33:33.040
[Guest]: office. That's my God, I can't afford that. And we wanted to break that for whatever reason,

01:33:33.040 --> 01:33:38.520
[Guest]: it almost came through, but it didn't happen. Maybe that's also a moment that sort of, you

01:33:38.520 --> 01:33:42.920
[Guest]: know, generated this thinking because you were this close and it didn't happen. Damn

01:33:42.920 --> 01:33:47.840
[Guest]: it. We have to persuade the political parties by more than mere logical persuasion, but

01:33:47.840 --> 01:33:53.220
[Amit Varma]: by the vote, the fear of the water. So, you know, so when you as coming from as someone

01:33:53.220 --> 01:33:59.560
[Amit Varma]: who's sort of new into politics and is coming from civil society, when you speak to politicians,

01:33:59.560 --> 01:34:03.600
[Amit Varma]: when you entered that game where you're speaking to politicians and trying to convince them

01:34:03.600 --> 01:34:09.080
[Amit Varma]: of policies and you know, we should do this and we should do that. Does the manner of

01:34:09.080 --> 01:34:15.540
[Amit Varma]: your discourse changes? Like, do you have to tailor your arguments to their incentives?

01:34:15.540 --> 01:34:22.640
[Guest]: What are those conversations? I speak exactly the way I'm speaking with you. No lies, no

01:34:22.640 --> 01:34:32.300
[Guest]: deception, no big talk, nonjudgmental and with genuine respect, because I believe they

01:34:32.300 --> 01:34:37.360
[Guest]: deserve genuine respect and a deep understanding and sympathy for the plight in which they

01:34:37.360 --> 01:34:42.520
[Guest]: are, whether it's vote buying or the wrong kind of candidates. It's not because they're

01:34:42.520 --> 01:34:47.760
[Guest]: bad. They have no choice. Now I'll give you two examples. In Andhra Pradesh, Mrs. Sonia

01:34:47.760 --> 01:34:53.100
[Guest]: Gandhi and Congress Party at one stage decided that after Mr. Dr. Rajasekar Reddy's passing,

01:34:53.100 --> 01:34:56.800
[Guest]: the son who wanted to be chief minister instantly, they felt it's not right. Let me at least

01:34:56.800 --> 01:35:01.240
[Guest]: have some chance. You can, while they were all for dynastic politics, Congress are running

01:35:01.240 --> 01:35:07.120
[Guest]: the opposite dynastic politics. They thought it was too, what should I say, too crass.

01:35:07.120 --> 01:35:11.120
[Guest]: And therefore, they did what they thought was the right thing. They paid a humongous

01:35:11.120 --> 01:35:19.800
[Guest]: price forever, possibly forever. In Karnataka, BJP asked Mr. Yadavirappa, then chief minister,

01:35:19.800 --> 01:35:25.800
[Guest]: to resign on moral grounds. The party paid a humongous price. It was not forever because

01:35:25.800 --> 01:35:29.920
[Guest]: Yadavirappa came back and BJP patched up and now again they're in power. So when the parties

01:35:29.920 --> 01:35:34.680
[Guest]: do the right thing that you and I, all the moralists and intelligentsia want, the price

01:35:34.680 --> 01:35:41.200
[Guest]: they pay is quite humongous. We must understand and sympathize and therefore create conditions

01:35:41.200 --> 01:35:48.080
[Guest]: where doing the right thing is also not politically suicidal. You be respectful of their genuine

01:35:48.080 --> 01:35:54.000
[Guest]: compulsions. And then while advancing an argument, while you are on the lookout for public interest

01:35:54.000 --> 01:36:00.000
[Guest]: and persuade them on that, don't be stupid and ask them to commit harakiri. That is one

01:36:00.000 --> 01:36:05.440
[Guest]: thing that tailoring, if it's required, it's not untruthful. It's not secret. It's not

01:36:05.440 --> 01:36:10.360
[Guest]: some magical thing. It's open. But honestly, this is also an advantage for you. Like for

01:36:10.360 --> 01:36:16.520
[Guest]: instance, if your vote share is below a certain threshold, to retain that, if you alter the

01:36:16.520 --> 01:36:20.160
[Guest]: system, you actually benefit. Otherwise, in the long term, maybe you'll lose out. It's

01:36:20.160 --> 01:36:27.320
[Guest]: a very honest argument. Why didn't it go through? This is the first time I'm stating it publicly.

01:36:27.320 --> 01:36:34.460
[Guest]: At the time the UPA was in power, the communists leftist had about 64 or 65 seats collectively.

01:36:34.460 --> 01:36:38.600
[Guest]: And if they wanted it, and they wanted it, communists always wanted a proportionality

01:36:38.600 --> 01:36:43.760
[Guest]: system for instance. If they wanted it, that was the time because Congress party would

01:36:43.760 --> 01:36:49.880
[Guest]: do anything to retain power. You know, the DNA of Congress, that is that once, you know,

01:36:49.880 --> 01:36:54.600
[Guest]: Mr. P. V. Narasimha Rao said, Congress is a party with the promise of power. Those were

01:36:54.600 --> 01:36:59.160
[Guest]: the days. But today, of course, BJP is the party with the promise of power. So that is

01:36:59.160 --> 01:37:06.400
[Guest]: the DNA. Somehow bring some consciences, somehow do whatever it takes to stay in power, etc.

01:37:06.400 --> 01:37:11.920
[Guest]: We persuaded the Congress party, very emphatically. I mean, they saw the data and they knew. BJP

01:37:11.920 --> 01:37:16.280
[Guest]: at some level were interacting with people and they also understood. And at that time,

01:37:16.280 --> 01:37:19.640
[Guest]: they were in disarray. Nobody expected Mr. Vajpayee's defeat in 2004. I didn't expect

01:37:19.640 --> 01:37:25.640
[Guest]: it. I don't think many people really anticipated that. It was a shocker. So they were in disarray.

01:37:25.640 --> 01:37:30.840
[Guest]: They also realized that no, something needs to be done. Then Mrs. Gandhi said, I'm completely

01:37:30.840 --> 01:37:35.560
[Guest]: persuaded. I'm excited, actually. I understand the problem now and how to address this. And

01:37:35.560 --> 01:37:39.160
[Guest]: after I don't want to go into too many details of the conversation, said, I'll talk to my

01:37:39.160 --> 01:37:43.760
[Guest]: colleagues and get back. After a month, Mrs. Gandhi said, you know, our colleagues are

01:37:43.760 --> 01:37:47.040
[Guest]: saying, Madam, we are in power, why bother about all this? Because you know, there's

01:37:47.040 --> 01:37:52.320
[Guest]: a status quoism embedded in that party. The differentiator would have been the communists.

01:37:52.320 --> 01:37:58.800
[Guest]: I pleaded with the communists, particularly CPM leadership, Prakash Karat, repeatedly,

01:37:58.800 --> 01:38:03.000
[Guest]: repeatedly. Each time the response is we are completely in favor, but we will not raise

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:09.120
[Guest]: our voice for this. If Congress party is on board, publicly gives a statement in favor

01:38:09.120 --> 01:38:13.120
[Guest]: of this and saying that we are going to do it, we want your support, then we will join

01:38:13.120 --> 01:38:17.720
[Guest]: the bandwagon. I told them, look, it's a status quo is to set up. It will not happen that

01:38:17.720 --> 01:38:22.400
[Guest]: it's a fundamental change, institutional change and incentives change. And you believe it's

01:38:22.400 --> 01:38:26.640
[Guest]: right for the country, you believe it's good for your parties also. So please do it. They

01:38:26.640 --> 01:38:33.560
[Guest]: chose not to do it. Why? I can only conjecture. And I'm reasonably confident that that is

01:38:33.560 --> 01:38:43.080
[Guest]: a correct assessment. They wrongly wanted to use their political capital for other purposes,

01:38:43.080 --> 01:38:49.280
[Guest]: stopping economic liberalization, WTO agreement, into American nuclear agreement, and many

01:38:49.280 --> 01:38:55.040
[Guest]: other things. And they felt that by using this ammunition for this cause, they will

01:38:55.040 --> 01:39:00.920
[Guest]: not have the ammunition left. I think it was a terrible strategic blunder. And of course,

01:39:00.920 --> 01:39:04.600
[Guest]: they paid a humongous price. But I think the country is paying a humongous price.

01:39:04.600 --> 01:39:08.400
[Amit Varma]: How would our politics have looked different if that had gone through?

01:39:08.400 --> 01:39:12.320
[Guest]: Three things would happen. Number one, the kind of people who are entering the political

01:39:12.320 --> 01:39:18.480
[Guest]: office now, why are they entering? They're not entering to be legislators. They're entering

01:39:18.480 --> 01:39:22.960
[Guest]: to have a finger in the executive pie. And they're using money power, organizational

01:39:22.960 --> 01:39:26.900
[Guest]: ability, and caste power as the levers. These are the three things that really are the determinants

01:39:26.900 --> 01:39:30.600
[Guest]: of who gets the seat, whether it's BJP or Congress, some other party, doesn't matter.

01:39:30.600 --> 01:39:36.040
[Guest]: These are the three broad things. Criminality is not always the consideration. We often

01:39:36.040 --> 01:39:40.040
[Guest]: talk because we're angry with politicians, we talk of criminality. Even criminality,

01:39:40.040 --> 01:39:46.520
[Guest]: when that background is there, it is because criminality brought the money power, organization,

01:39:46.520 --> 01:39:52.680
[Guest]: and almost every criminal who became a significant politician, styled himself as a caste leader,

01:39:52.680 --> 01:39:57.120
[Guest]: or sometimes a community leader, religious leader. So criminality is not the fundamental.

01:39:57.120 --> 01:40:02.200
[Guest]: It is the other three things that happen along with criminality. And therefore, the incentives

01:40:02.200 --> 01:40:06.320
[Guest]: are wrongly aligned. We're buying money, once you spend that kind of money, it takes us

01:40:06.320 --> 01:40:10.880
[Guest]: so high. I mean, in some of the states like in the South and the West, 20-30 crores for

01:40:10.880 --> 01:40:16.400
[Guest]: an assembly constituency. Even in the Northeast, for a Lok Sabha seat, sometimes 30-40 crores,

01:40:16.400 --> 01:40:19.360
[Guest]: absurd amounts, obscene amounts, unheard of amounts anywhere in the world.

01:40:19.360 --> 01:40:22.000
[Guest]: And you have to get an ROI somehow after that.

01:40:22.000 --> 01:40:25.760
[Guest]: Otherwise, you have no choice. See, after spending that, you will not be elected, but

01:40:25.760 --> 01:40:31.840
[Guest]: you are now in contention, serious, it's an entry fee. Now, once you have a proportionality

01:40:31.840 --> 01:40:37.760
[Guest]: model, for instance, with a slate of candidates, and the party's success depends on the proportion

01:40:37.760 --> 01:40:43.760
[Guest]: of votes you get, not who wins in a constituency, neither vote buying and money power of that

01:40:43.760 --> 01:40:52.880
[Guest]: kind, nor the other highly misplaced policies in order to get another 200,000 votes.

01:40:52.880 --> 01:40:59.800
[Guest]: For instance, in recent elections in several states, many parties very unwisely offered

01:40:59.800 --> 01:41:05.600
[Guest]: that they will scrap the new pension scheme. You know, because the salaries, the pensions

01:41:05.600 --> 01:41:10.440
[Guest]: are now outstripping salaries, industry pensions, and therefore, often you're getting much more

01:41:10.440 --> 01:41:16.680
[Guest]: than your last salary drawn as pension, and your lifespans are expanding happily.

01:41:16.680 --> 01:41:21.440
[Guest]: There's a stage where the future generations are forced to pay for the services in the

01:41:21.440 --> 01:41:25.600
[Guest]: past. So quite wisely, the union government sat with all political parties and the state

01:41:25.600 --> 01:41:29.040
[Guest]: governments and came up with a new pension program, which is necessary for the country.

01:41:29.040 --> 01:41:34.160
[Guest]: But because you're afraid that you lose those 100,000 votes or 200,000 votes in a state,

01:41:34.160 --> 01:41:38.000
[Guest]: in a first possible system, then their families are enough, maybe to put you this way or that

01:41:38.000 --> 01:41:43.000
[Guest]: way, in the desperate gamble, they will not offer that this is the way the system operates

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:48.560
[Guest]: in a take all system. Here in the proportionality model, you're not worried about that.

01:41:48.560 --> 01:41:54.560
[Guest]: And once the incentives for the political party and the candidate are dramatically altered,

01:41:54.560 --> 01:41:57.400
[Guest]: and once the people realize that each vote counts, and therefore, I don't have to vote

01:41:57.400 --> 01:42:02.560
[Guest]: for quote unquote winner, there's no winner. Each vote actually has a value in terms of

01:42:02.560 --> 01:42:07.960
[Guest]: representation, it will be a significant change in the way things happen. That's not the only

01:42:07.960 --> 01:42:11.720
[Guest]: way you can transform India right now, I don't think that's possible. Because when Mr. Narendra

01:42:11.720 --> 01:42:19.040
[Guest]: Modi is winning everything that he fights, when a political party is dominant, and they're

01:42:19.040 --> 01:42:24.240
[Guest]: getting disproportionate representation, as Congress did for a long time, there's no incentive

01:42:24.240 --> 01:42:28.720
[Guest]: for them to switch over. Perhaps now, the model we have to think about is can we think

01:42:28.720 --> 01:42:33.440
[Guest]: of clear separation of the executive and legislature, a direct direction of the leader because anyway,

01:42:33.440 --> 01:42:39.240
[Guest]: people vote for Narendra Modi and for KCR and for Jagan or somebody, they're not voting

01:42:39.240 --> 01:42:44.640
[Guest]: for a party in most of the cases. And therefore, you actually make it legally and institutionally

01:42:44.640 --> 01:42:50.440
[Guest]: so so that some of the burdens that today's system imposes on the leaders, namely, how

01:42:50.440 --> 01:42:54.520
[Guest]: can the fellow get elected in the constituency and therefore have all these qualities rather

01:42:54.520 --> 01:42:59.000
[Guest]: than good representation. You depend on them for survival in office, any day they can bring

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:03.080
[Guest]: you down and therefore do their bidding, all the misgovernance, interference from court

01:43:03.080 --> 01:43:08.400
[Guest]: cases to contracts to transfers to postings, you know, endemic all over the country. And

01:43:08.400 --> 01:43:12.960
[Guest]: your ministerial positions are dependent only on the legislature. Therefore, everything

01:43:12.960 --> 01:43:17.920
[Guest]: is about fighting for crumbs rather than looking for the best people to govern. And because

01:43:17.920 --> 01:43:22.680
[Guest]: the legislators see local governments as a threat in a system where power is highly centralized

01:43:22.680 --> 01:43:27.040
[Guest]: entrenched, you don't dare to empower local governments where tomorrow legislator does

01:43:27.040 --> 01:43:30.480
[Guest]: not matter in that sense. And the people who want to legislate is actually go to local

01:43:30.480 --> 01:43:34.360
[Guest]: governments and lead them if you empower local government, so the incentives will be altered.

01:43:34.360 --> 01:43:39.280
[Guest]: So you have to figure out how to alter the incentives. And the levers of change you must

01:43:39.280 --> 01:43:43.840
[Guest]: look at. And I believe there's a possibility now, let us see if that works. And I believe

01:43:43.840 --> 01:43:47.960
[Guest]: some people are looking at that then you're running dispensation. And if that is true,

01:43:47.960 --> 01:43:51.280
[Guest]: I think we must help them structure it properly and sell it well in the country and then make

01:43:51.280 --> 01:43:52.280
[Guest]: change happen.

01:43:52.280 --> 01:43:56.960
[Amit Varma]: So over your time in politics, I mean, this is obviously something that almost happened.

01:43:56.960 --> 01:44:00.240
[Amit Varma]: But if you if you look back on your time in politics, what are the things you're proud

01:44:00.240 --> 01:44:04.760
[Amit Varma]: of your triumphs, and some of them might well be silent, low key triumphs, which are not,

01:44:04.760 --> 01:44:07.240
[Guest]: you know, publicly sort of hailed?

01:44:07.240 --> 01:44:13.360
[Guest]: Let me expand this question to the larger public advocacy. First, a caveat in terms

01:44:13.360 --> 01:44:17.840
[Guest]: of what we've been able to accomplish as a group, we probably are the biggest in the

01:44:17.840 --> 01:44:23.920
[Guest]: country. That's because the bar is very low, and there's not much that's been accomplished.

01:44:23.920 --> 01:44:27.920
[Guest]: But I'm always mindful that in the context of what needs to happen, what we accomplished

01:44:27.920 --> 01:44:31.560
[Guest]: is still minuscule, though it's bigger than almost any other group, perhaps in the world

01:44:31.560 --> 01:44:36.240
[Guest]: without political power. I mean, three constitutional amendments, seven or eight significant laws

01:44:36.240 --> 01:44:40.160
[Guest]: and four or five major policy changes, including 2g spectrum license cancellation through court

01:44:40.160 --> 01:44:48.120
[Guest]: intervention, disclosure of candidate details, law, local courts, law, etc, etc. And removing

01:44:48.120 --> 01:44:54.920
[Guest]: the export ban on food grains, I don't understand what EDSC made us impose that ban, a removal

01:44:54.920 --> 01:45:01.200
[Guest]: of trade barriers within the country, food grains, etc. I can go on and on. But in the

01:45:01.200 --> 01:45:08.760
[Guest]: largest scheme, these are still minuscule. As a legislator, obviously, I could do some

01:45:08.760 --> 01:45:12.960
[Guest]: things, more things to prevent damage from happening rather than making good happen,

01:45:12.960 --> 01:45:16.840
[Guest]: because it's easier to prevent damage from happening. If you have a sufficiently strong

01:45:16.840 --> 01:45:22.600
[Guest]: and credible voice, and they respect you, it's harder to actually make the ruling party

01:45:22.600 --> 01:45:27.240
[Guest]: agree to do the right thing. So there's a clash. Therefore, when they tried to bring

01:45:27.240 --> 01:45:32.760
[Guest]: in a terrible and draconian societies law, even British government during their time,

01:45:32.760 --> 01:45:36.560
[Guest]: they had an extremely liberal law, single handedly, I could block it. I mean, they simply

01:45:36.560 --> 01:45:41.560
[Guest]: did not know how to counter my opposition. I was a lone opponent on that. Several such

01:45:41.560 --> 01:45:47.080
[Guest]: things I can cite, but the particular context in which I was a legislator in this state,

01:45:47.080 --> 01:45:52.400
[Guest]: the state was really driven by this Andhra Telangana thing. And therefore, mine was one

01:45:52.400 --> 01:45:57.040
[Guest]: of the few voices of sanity, trying to bring people together and reconcile conflicting

01:45:57.040 --> 01:46:02.820
[Guest]: emotions. I don't think I succeeded. But I think that voice was loud and clear and widely

01:46:02.820 --> 01:46:07.600
[Guest]: understood. And increasingly, that voice has greater credibility today. Because post those

01:46:07.600 --> 01:46:12.360
[Guest]: incidents, people have both the states realize that that is what was required. And they simply

01:46:12.360 --> 01:46:15.880
[Amit Varma]: were falling prey to to emotionalism.

01:46:15.880 --> 01:46:21.080
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of sort of the landscape of Indian politics, it seems to me number one, that

01:46:21.080 --> 01:46:27.920
[Amit Varma]: most parties are really extremely similar, that is in their economics, a very statist

01:46:27.920 --> 01:46:34.480
[Amit Varma]: in as far as their approach towards society, it's often very dictated toward by identity

01:46:34.480 --> 01:46:40.000
[Amit Varma]: and vote bank politics. And, you know, as Arun Shourie once famously said, you know,

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:46.720
[Amit Varma]: the NDA is UPA plus cow, and the Congress also has embraced the cow in various places.

01:46:46.720 --> 01:46:50.680
[Amit Varma]: Given this, it would seem and also given the large number of people who don't actually

01:46:50.680 --> 01:46:57.720
[Amit Varma]: vote, or who vote voter, it would also seem that there is scope for disruption. And in

01:46:57.720 --> 01:47:03.000
[Amit Varma]: a sense, when you enter the electoral marketplace, you must have thought of perhaps being a disruptive

01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:07.960
[Amit Varma]: influence and definitely whatever one thinks of the Aam Aadmi Party, I'm not a big fan,

01:47:07.960 --> 01:47:12.440
[Amit Varma]: but whatever one thinks of them, what they did very successfully as political entrepreneurs,

01:47:12.440 --> 01:47:17.040
[Amit Varma]: was it disrupted that marketplace and made that space for themselves, which is pretty

01:47:17.040 --> 01:47:23.760
[Amit Varma]: remarkable, but that was in the local political market of Delhi. So in general, given that

01:47:23.760 --> 01:47:28.400
[Amit Varma]: politics has become so ossified, that all the parties are just more of the same, do

01:47:28.400 --> 01:47:33.560
[Amit Varma]: you think that there is scope for disruption? And if so, I mean, I know politics and the

01:47:33.560 --> 01:47:37.960
[Amit Varma]: future are both story of unknown unknowns, and a week is a long time in politics, as

01:47:37.960 --> 01:47:43.120
[Amit Varma]: is famously said, but what are the possible avenues through which such disruption can

01:47:43.120 --> 01:47:48.040
[Guest]: come? If cities are empowered, like in Delhi, let's say Mumbai has a genuine self governance

01:47:48.040 --> 01:47:53.280
[Guest]: and the mayor of Mumbai and the Council of Mumbai actually matter on their own. I'm absolutely

01:47:53.280 --> 01:47:58.480
[Guest]: certain that something even bigger will happen in Mumbai, or Bengaluru, may not be on the

01:47:58.480 --> 01:48:03.080
[Guest]: same scale, but Hyderabad and Chennai and others will also follow. But it's a big if

01:48:03.080 --> 01:48:10.640
[Guest]: unfortunately, we are not giving ourselves that chance. Once I asked the then Prime Minister,

01:48:10.640 --> 01:48:16.840
[Guest]: so can you name the name of mayor of Delhi? He could not, of course, I could not either.

01:48:16.840 --> 01:48:22.240
[Guest]: Or Chennai or Bengaluru or Mumbai or something I said, then can you name the mayor of London

01:48:22.240 --> 01:48:28.080
[Guest]: at the time, Boris Johnson was the mayor, the current Prime Minister, Mayor of New York,

01:48:28.080 --> 01:48:34.240
[Guest]: New York, Bloomberg or somebody. Earlier, the current mix co-president was mayor. He

01:48:34.240 --> 01:48:38.640
[Guest]: could name some of them. I said, aren't we ashamed? We know the names of mayors of other

01:48:38.640 --> 01:48:43.280
[Guest]: cities in the rest of the world. In India, we don't know the mayor of a single city.

01:48:43.280 --> 01:48:48.720
[Guest]: In 1924, some of the biggest names in India were leaders of local governments. Rajendra

01:48:48.720 --> 01:48:57.120
[Guest]: Prasad in Patna, Jawaharlal Nehru, Chitranjan Das and later, Subhash Chandra Bose, Sardar

01:48:57.120 --> 01:49:04.680
[Guest]: Vallabhbhai Patel. And even much earlier, in Salem, Chakravartin Rajagopalachari or

01:49:04.680 --> 01:49:11.200
[Guest]: even before him, our own Prakasham Pantulu in Rajahmundry. So, you know, local governments

01:49:11.200 --> 01:49:17.080
[Guest]: during British India were far more powerful and nurtured leadership than in independent

01:49:17.080 --> 01:49:23.120
[Guest]: India. Actually, I feel ashamed to say this, but it is absolute truth. If that happens,

01:49:23.120 --> 01:49:28.440
[Guest]: then there is a lever. In the absence of that, I think the cities can start shouting, making

01:49:28.440 --> 01:49:34.380
[Guest]: their voice felt. If Mumbaikars say, I don't care if it's BJP or Shiv Sena and CP or Congress.

01:49:34.380 --> 01:49:39.400
[Guest]: If you don't allow Mumbai to have self-government within reasonable limits, we are going to

01:49:39.400 --> 01:49:45.040
[Guest]: vote against you. If that voice is felt strongly, I think there is an option, there is an option

01:49:45.040 --> 01:49:50.120
[Guest]: but that means you have to overcome the primordial loyalties. I think parties will listen. At

01:49:50.120 --> 01:49:55.320
[Guest]: the very least, you must start a framework for the big cities so that they can set the

01:49:55.320 --> 01:50:01.920
[Guest]: trend. Barring that, as I mentioned to you earlier, if a well-meaning government, if

01:50:01.920 --> 01:50:06.360
[Guest]: they have at least half wisdom, if they are at least fiscally empowered with adequate

01:50:06.360 --> 01:50:09.640
[Guest]: accountability so that the levers still are with you, you're not losing control because

01:50:09.640 --> 01:50:13.760
[Guest]: they're afraid of losing control. Sometimes it's legitimate concerns. I also respect that.

01:50:13.760 --> 01:50:17.280
[Guest]: Many people say, look, almost everything you say, we agree, but local governments, you're

01:50:17.280 --> 01:50:21.480
[Guest]: too romantic. No, there is almost corruption, which is true. I'm not denying it. There's

01:50:21.480 --> 01:50:24.800
[Guest]: vote buying, which is true. I'm not denying it. But you have all those things. You can't

01:50:24.800 --> 01:50:30.080
[Guest]: use that as an argument. But even then, I don't want to say that. You hold them to account.

01:50:30.080 --> 01:50:33.880
[Guest]: Create strong accountability instruments and keep them broadly under your supervision.

01:50:33.880 --> 01:50:38.160
[Guest]: I have no quarrel with that. I think if you create that framework, at least in cities,

01:50:38.160 --> 01:50:43.560
[Guest]: I don't think it will happen easily in villages for two reasons. One, it's much bigger. Parties

01:50:43.560 --> 01:50:48.200
[Guest]: don't want to lose control. Two, and this is a very sad statement I'm making, I grew

01:50:48.200 --> 01:50:56.360
[Guest]: up in a village. Given the way our economy has progressed over the years, there's nothing

01:50:56.360 --> 01:51:02.020
[Guest]: of leadership left in villages. There is neither money nor talent available in villages. Almost

01:51:02.020 --> 01:51:08.440
[Guest]: anybody who has ambition and ability had to necessarily migrate to urban areas. And therefore,

01:51:08.440 --> 01:51:14.680
[Guest]: in the current local governments in the village, unless you establish larger local units, not

01:51:14.680 --> 01:51:19.160
[Guest]: a village panchayat of 2000 population, not 1.5 million or a million panchayats, all this

01:51:19.160 --> 01:51:24.360
[Guest]: is, in my judgment, a very romantic, silly notion. If you create larger entities like

01:51:24.360 --> 01:51:28.520
[Guest]: Kerala has done, and then empower, then rural areas also similar thing is possible. But

01:51:28.520 --> 01:51:33.960
[Guest]: right now, I don't see that. Urban area, people for the first time are aware that they're

01:51:33.960 --> 01:51:41.480
[Guest]: paying taxes. And urban local governments largely self sustained. And people are increasingly

01:51:41.480 --> 01:51:46.920
[Guest]: angry that despite paying property taxes, my services are very poor. They're angry.

01:51:46.920 --> 01:51:52.520
[Guest]: I think if that can be harnessed, I think that can be potentially transformational thing.

01:51:52.520 --> 01:51:56.160
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about how things can change, you say the people of Mumbai raise their voice

01:51:56.160 --> 01:52:02.120
[Amit Varma]: for the people of, you know, Chennai raise their voice or whatever, in your time in general,

01:52:02.120 --> 01:52:08.120
[Amit Varma]: how has the expression of politics within civil society changed? Is do you find civil

01:52:08.120 --> 01:52:13.640
[Amit Varma]: society expressing itself more or less? Is technology somewhat of a factor in that that

01:52:13.640 --> 01:52:18.240
[Amit Varma]: it becomes possible for so many people who otherwise would not have had a platform or

01:52:18.240 --> 01:52:21.720
[Amit Varma]: a megaphone to actually go on Twitter or wherever and express

01:52:21.720 --> 01:52:26.320
[Guest]: undoubtedly reaching out to people and mobilizing people is much easier than it was when I started

01:52:26.320 --> 01:52:32.200
[Guest]: in 1996. After leaving the civil service, I mean, I remember the amount of hardship

01:52:32.200 --> 01:52:36.600
[Guest]: you had to undergo even for the simplest things. And today, in a jiffy, we can reach people.

01:52:36.600 --> 01:52:41.440
[Guest]: But also, things have gotten infinitely worse in some other respect. At that time, and I'm

01:52:41.440 --> 01:52:48.800
[Guest]: saying that serious sense of responsibility. A lot of middle classes are able to and willing

01:52:48.800 --> 01:52:56.920
[Guest]: to go beyond caste, religion, religion and party. Even if they are committed to a particular

01:52:56.920 --> 01:53:00.600
[Guest]: party, they're willing to look beyond that for the larger good of India, they were willing

01:53:00.600 --> 01:53:06.600
[Guest]: to buy that argument and articulate that argument. Today, that capacity is significantly diminished,

01:53:06.600 --> 01:53:12.920
[Guest]: because we're much more polarized, much more acerbic, much more volatile, and much more

01:53:12.920 --> 01:53:19.280
[Amit Varma]: hate filled. That is scary. No, and I was at an event last evening where I was talking

01:53:19.280 --> 01:53:25.800
[Amit Varma]: about how even if liberalism has been failed by politics, it can still be enabled by technology

01:53:25.800 --> 01:53:30.720
[Amit Varma]: like technology enables individual freedom and enables us in so many ways. And then one

01:53:30.720 --> 01:53:35.680
[Amit Varma]: person from the audience shut me up very wisely by pointing out that look what happened in

01:53:35.680 --> 01:53:41.040
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir, that where the power of the state being what it is, sure, all the technology

01:53:41.040 --> 01:53:45.360
[Amit Varma]: is there, but they're not even allowed to go on the internet. So what is still a special

01:53:45.360 --> 01:53:49.240
[Guest]: situation, I would not be alarmist about that, because I would still say because of the historical

01:53:49.240 --> 01:53:55.040
[Guest]: legacy and torturous history and, and the passions, etc. But even otherwise, even where

01:53:55.040 --> 01:54:01.080
[Guest]: there are no constraints on the use of technology or your freedoms in general, what has happened

01:54:01.080 --> 01:54:10.320
[Guest]: is political parties have almost become the new castes. The rigidity that was there throughout

01:54:10.320 --> 01:54:14.320
[Guest]: our history in our caste system, which is hopefully sort of breaking down a little bit

01:54:14.320 --> 01:54:20.320
[Guest]: in the past 50 or 100 years. Political parties that degree of rigidity, there's no willingness

01:54:20.320 --> 01:54:26.900
[Guest]: to listen to the other person. There's no willingness to look at the issues beyond personalities.

01:54:26.900 --> 01:54:31.400
[Guest]: If you admit for my like you, I agree with you, then whatever you say is right doesn't

01:54:31.400 --> 01:54:36.840
[Guest]: matter how stupid or idiotic it is. If I don't like you, if I don't like your face for whatever

01:54:36.840 --> 01:54:42.760
[Guest]: reason, then no matter how wise and wonderful and useful to me it is, I'm not going to listen.

01:54:42.760 --> 01:54:46.720
[Guest]: So that's a very dangerous situation. I think in a very significant measure, I don't think

01:54:46.720 --> 01:54:51.120
[Guest]: that is the whole of India. But I think that is the dominant part of India locally right

01:54:51.120 --> 01:54:55.280
[Guest]: now. And I think in many other countries, I don't think United States is different.

01:54:55.280 --> 01:54:58.880
[Guest]: It's as messed up as we are, but they can afford that mess, because they're at a much

01:54:58.880 --> 01:55:03.520
[Guest]: higher level of evolution and their local governments are so strong. Ultimately, if

01:55:03.520 --> 01:55:07.320
[Guest]: you take away a federal government and the basic headlines, their lives will not be altered.

01:55:07.320 --> 01:55:11.680
[Guest]: Whereas in our country, I think we are in a grave danger. We are completely ignoring

01:55:11.680 --> 01:55:15.120
[Guest]: things that actually matter to us and paying a heavy price.

01:55:15.120 --> 01:55:19.200
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, there's a term popularized by the social scientist Cass Sunstein, which

01:55:19.200 --> 01:55:24.040
[Amit Varma]: describes this very beautifully, it's group polarization. And, you know, he and his fellow

01:55:24.040 --> 01:55:28.960
[Amit Varma]: researchers had carried out an experiment where they took people with specific views,

01:55:28.960 --> 01:55:32.800
[Amit Varma]: like a bunch of conservatives or a bunch of liberals and put them in a room. And they

01:55:32.800 --> 01:55:37.920
[Amit Varma]: found that at the end of a session of interacting with each other, the views of the group as

01:55:37.920 --> 01:55:43.360
[Amit Varma]: a whole, had shifted beyond the most extreme individual in the group, which he called group

01:55:43.360 --> 01:55:49.240
[Amit Varma]: polarization. And what because they are reinforcing each other, and they are each then also sort

01:55:49.240 --> 01:55:53.680
[Amit Varma]: of signaling to each other how true they are to their cause, and so on. And what the internet

01:55:53.680 --> 01:55:59.600
[Amit Varma]: does is that it enables this at scale. So you have this group polarization happening

01:55:59.600 --> 01:56:04.120
[Amit Varma]: at scale, these giant echo chambers where everyone is posturing to raise their stature

01:56:04.120 --> 01:56:09.080
[Amit Varma]: within their in group. And soon what happens is that issues don't matter. It's it's, it's

01:56:09.080 --> 01:56:14.560
[Amit Varma]: a complete tribal war. And, you know, one of the ways in which I gauge whether a person

01:56:14.560 --> 01:56:21.120
[Amit Varma]: is thinking about politics deeply, is whether their support of a politician of a party or

01:56:21.120 --> 01:56:27.760
[Amit Varma]: opposition to a party is absolute or is contingent around specific issues. You know, I remember

01:56:27.760 --> 01:56:37.240
[Amit Varma]: people who would criticize the BJP for opposing FDA in retail, continuing to criticize them

01:56:37.240 --> 01:56:42.600
[Amit Varma]: after they allowed it. You know, so the whatever you do, whatever you do, right? Yeah, you

01:56:42.600 --> 01:56:47.920
[Amit Varma]: are the enemy, you are the other, you know, and there's nothing that can happen about

01:56:47.920 --> 01:56:51.840
[Guest]: this. It's a very troublesome thing. And I'm sure that senior leadership in all parties

01:56:51.840 --> 01:56:58.280
[Guest]: is aware, whether it's Narendra Modi, or Mrs. Sonia Gandhi, or Sharath Pawar, or many others.

01:56:58.280 --> 01:57:03.560
[Guest]: But I think they're also in many ways helpless, because if you antagonize the base too much,

01:57:03.560 --> 01:57:09.640
[Guest]: then you lose your foundations. If you allow them a free rein, then you lose the very purpose.

01:57:09.640 --> 01:57:15.000
[Guest]: I think we are now in that very dangerous phase. Let's hope sanity will prevail. I really

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:20.280
[Guest]: don't have an easy answer to this. And what you're doing, that's why it's amazing that

01:57:20.280 --> 01:57:24.160
[Guest]: actually people are willing to listen to an issue beyond parties without categorizing

01:57:24.160 --> 01:57:29.320
[Guest]: Amit Verma or JP or somebody else. Are you BJP? Are you Congress? Are you Hindutva? Are

01:57:29.320 --> 01:57:34.600
[Guest]: you anti-Hindutva? Without categorizing that you're able to engage the attention of a significant

01:57:34.600 --> 01:57:40.480
[Guest]: number of people in a thoughtful discussion. I think that's an incredible thing. I don't

01:57:40.480 --> 01:57:44.200
[Guest]: know how far this can spread or many such efforts can be made. But this is one small

01:57:44.200 --> 01:57:46.680
[Guest]: little contribution you and I can make.

01:57:46.680 --> 01:57:51.080
[Amit Varma]: How was your journey in electoral politics? Like you were earlier in politics of the other

01:57:51.080 --> 01:57:54.720
[Amit Varma]: kind, the kind of politics we are engaging in, where you try to convince people and change

01:57:54.720 --> 01:57:58.760
[Amit Varma]: hearts and minds. And then you enter electoral politics, where you're actually going up in

01:57:58.760 --> 01:58:03.320
[Amit Varma]: front of people and saying, hey, vote for me. One, was there any dissonance there? Was

01:58:03.320 --> 01:58:09.040
[Amit Varma]: it hard for you as a person as a thinker to actually go out there and do that? And two,

01:58:09.040 --> 01:58:13.800
[Amit Varma]: what was that whole experience like? Did it in some sense disillusion you about?

01:58:13.800 --> 01:58:19.640
[Guest]: Not at all. Not at all. You see, unlike in the marketplace, in the political marketplace

01:58:19.640 --> 01:58:25.880
[Guest]: in our electoral system, it's all or none. But if you actually take that out and look

01:58:25.880 --> 01:58:31.880
[Guest]: at the public support or their respect for these ideas or their willingness to consider,

01:58:31.880 --> 01:58:36.800
[Guest]: then it's a huge success. But because of electoral system compulsions and the political consequences,

01:58:36.800 --> 01:58:41.040
[Guest]: for instance, in 2014, despite everything else, there was a realistic chance that I

01:58:41.040 --> 01:58:44.440
[Guest]: would have been the representative of the people for the Lok Sabha. But because the

01:58:44.440 --> 01:58:48.000
[Guest]: unique situation in Andhra Pradesh, Telangana at the time, though that was still Andhra

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:53.240
[Guest]: Pradesh, but Telangana was already decided and the date was after post-election. I contested

01:58:53.240 --> 01:59:00.480
[Guest]: from Hyderabad city. Some significant political parties offered me space in some other places.

01:59:00.480 --> 01:59:04.880
[Guest]: They would have got me elected, but I decided not to use that because even if I stay away

01:59:04.880 --> 01:59:08.640
[Guest]: from that, they would still be indulging in the normal practices and I didn't want that

01:59:08.640 --> 01:59:15.160
[Guest]: way. I said, if I have to make an impact, it has to be not being merely a legislator

01:59:15.160 --> 01:59:21.000
[Guest]: or a parliamentarian, but the way I want it to be. Any other way is not worthwhile. Now,

01:59:21.000 --> 01:59:25.080
[Guest]: the reason why ultimately that didn't work out is my constituents, the largest in India

01:59:25.080 --> 01:59:31.080
[Guest]: at that time in terms of electorate strength. The people of Telangana origin, they could

01:59:31.080 --> 01:59:36.600
[Guest]: see that I am their best choice, but they were afraid that if they voted for me, their

01:59:36.600 --> 01:59:43.800
[Guest]: primary enemy at that time politically, TDP would win. The people of Andhra origin, they

01:59:43.800 --> 01:59:47.640
[Guest]: could see that I was their best choice. They were afraid that if they voted for me, their

01:59:47.640 --> 01:59:53.640
[Guest]: primary enemy, TRS would win. I got crushed between the two. That's one. Second, what

01:59:53.640 --> 01:59:59.520
[Guest]: did Narendra Modi do in India to many people like us in a political sense? What is the

01:59:59.520 --> 02:00:06.840
[Guest]: public perception of people like us? Now, we want to bring about some change, a honesty,

02:00:06.840 --> 02:00:12.960
[Guest]: be good governance. If you want to capture in two expressions, Narendra Modi in the eyes

02:00:12.960 --> 02:00:18.360
[Guest]: of the majority of the middle class and young people in the country embodied both whether

02:00:18.360 --> 02:00:23.240
[Guest]: delivery was there or not, you forget that. But in the popular imagination in 2014, he

02:00:23.240 --> 02:00:30.520
[Guest]: embodied these two. Therefore, our cloak was taken over by him. So between these two patterns,

02:00:30.520 --> 02:00:35.720
[Guest]: obviously, were rejected. So in our electoral system, electoral politics and outcomes are

02:00:35.720 --> 02:00:41.200
[Guest]: much too complex. It's not about you. We will be very arrogant and ignorant if we thought

02:00:41.200 --> 02:00:45.560
[Guest]: it's about you. It's about a process and a situation and a context.

02:00:45.560 --> 02:00:50.680
[Amit Varma]: The currents of history and society are too strong for any one person to fight. I have

02:00:50.680 --> 02:00:56.040
[Amit Varma]: some further sort of questions arising out of this. One is really a two part question.

02:00:56.040 --> 02:00:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And I often ask, I've asked this to guests who've, you know, been here to speak about

02:00:59.440 --> 02:01:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Indian politics and the BJP per se, which is that there seems to be a very interesting

02:01:04.320 --> 02:01:10.240
[Amit Varma]: duality at play. One is that the BJP is a one party that to some extent does embody

02:01:10.240 --> 02:01:15.040
[Amit Varma]: a particular ideology and a set of principles, whether one agrees with them or not. And those

02:01:15.040 --> 02:01:20.560
[Amit Varma]: that ideology and that set of principles has brought them very far. But on the other hand,

02:01:20.560 --> 02:01:26.080
[Amit Varma]: what you see in, say, the sort of political alliances and the maneuverings that Amit Shah

02:01:26.080 --> 02:01:32.160
[Amit Varma]: has done, who seems to me from a distance to be an absolutely brilliant political strategist,

02:01:32.160 --> 02:01:37.160
[Amit Varma]: he seems to embody the will to power, that we must come to power at any cost. If that

02:01:37.160 --> 02:01:43.240
[Amit Varma]: means alliances with people we otherwise abused, we will do that. If it means poaching people

02:01:43.240 --> 02:01:48.480
[Amit Varma]: from other parties, while till yesterday, we had set our IT cell on them, we will do

02:01:48.480 --> 02:01:52.960
[Amit Varma]: that also. And it seems to me at some level, and this is why it's a two part question,

02:01:52.960 --> 02:01:58.040
[Amit Varma]: because one, it's about the BJP that is there a conflict between their core ideology and

02:01:58.040 --> 02:02:02.480
[Amit Varma]: this will to power? And if so, how will it manifest? Will they become a bigger version,

02:02:02.480 --> 02:02:06.120
[Amit Varma]: a different version of what the Congress itself was once driven by nothing but the will to

02:02:06.120 --> 02:02:12.560
[Amit Varma]: power? And the second question is a broader question, and would apply even to you that,

02:02:12.560 --> 02:02:16.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, you might get into politics with a set of principles, but what you need to

02:02:16.280 --> 02:02:20.960
[Amit Varma]: survive is that will to power where compromises have to be made, such as the compromise you

02:02:20.960 --> 02:02:26.480
[Amit Varma]: mentioned you refuse to make when it came to taking the ticket of one party or the other.

02:02:26.480 --> 02:02:29.120
[Amit Varma]: How does one then reconcile that?

02:02:29.120 --> 02:02:34.160
[Guest]: Let me take the first question first. I think there are, there are many strands here. The

02:02:34.160 --> 02:02:40.960
[Guest]: first is, one of the great challenges of right wing parties all over the world is without

02:02:40.960 --> 02:02:47.200
[Guest]: taking a certain position, which may not be entirely modern and liberal, you cannot have

02:02:47.200 --> 02:02:55.200
[Guest]: the base with you. But without having the capacity to attract the economic liberals

02:02:55.200 --> 02:03:02.880
[Guest]: and the modernists, you cannot have a majority, nor can you actually take the country forward.

02:03:02.880 --> 02:03:08.200
[Guest]: The rest of the world grappled with that. Take the Christian Democrats in Germany, take

02:03:08.200 --> 02:03:14.600
[Guest]: the conservatives in the United States. Similarly, many Republicans in the United States and

02:03:14.600 --> 02:03:21.400
[Guest]: many others elsewhere, conservatives in Britain, etc, etc. I think India has this unique experience,

02:03:21.400 --> 02:03:25.560
[Guest]: new experience. And I think our leadership is grappling with that. They're not able to

02:03:25.560 --> 02:03:29.280
[Guest]: figure out what is the best way of doing that. But even elsewhere in the world, let's be

02:03:29.280 --> 02:03:34.280
[Guest]: fair. In recent times, the consensus we thought that existed suddenly is breaking down. Angela

02:03:34.280 --> 02:03:40.560
[Guest]: Merkel suddenly is now facing from AFD, the Nazi party, that the core is now moving some

02:03:40.560 --> 02:03:44.480
[Guest]: respect to that. And Republicans in the United States, suddenly we find that something strange

02:03:44.480 --> 02:03:49.960
[Guest]: is happening. So even there, after having solved the problem, they discovered the problem

02:03:49.960 --> 02:03:58.920
[Guest]: again comes back. Any country as complex and as, as shall I say, limited in democratic

02:03:58.920 --> 02:04:03.520
[Guest]: experience as India is, I think it's even a harder problem. I think we must understand

02:04:03.520 --> 02:04:07.320
[Guest]: that without being excessively judgmental. That is one broad thing. The second broad

02:04:07.320 --> 02:04:12.200
[Guest]: thing is that's what is disturbing. If Mr. Amit Shah and Mr. Narendra Modi are thinking

02:04:12.200 --> 02:04:15.280
[Guest]: of getting into power at any cost and will to power is there, will to power is necessary

02:04:15.280 --> 02:04:20.080
[Guest]: for politics. There's no question about it. But if will to power without purpose becomes

02:04:20.080 --> 02:04:25.160
[Guest]: the dominant feature, how are we different from the Congress regime? That's exactly the

02:04:25.160 --> 02:04:31.800
[Guest]: criticism against Congress for a long, long period. After the 1960s, the primary attack

02:04:31.800 --> 02:04:35.800
[Guest]: on Congress with complete justification was that there was a will to power without any

02:04:35.800 --> 02:04:41.760
[Guest]: purpose. If you become a clone of Congress, of course you will survive in power. Congress

02:04:41.760 --> 02:04:46.800
[Guest]: survived for 30, 40 years in power like that. But is that your purpose in life? Did Narendra

02:04:46.800 --> 02:04:53.840
[Guest]: Modi give up his personal life, his economic fortunes, and the many things that people

02:04:53.840 --> 02:05:00.400
[Guest]: treasure, his family and many things for a cause that he believed in passionately? Is

02:05:00.400 --> 02:05:07.040
[Guest]: this the net outcome? I think there's a question that many genuinely thoughtful people who

02:05:07.040 --> 02:05:12.800
[Guest]: care and cared for India deeply, they must ponder. I'm not questioning the need for power,

02:05:12.800 --> 02:05:18.480
[Guest]: but for power without purpose is the most dangerous thing. I think now there is a, there

02:05:18.480 --> 02:05:26.240
[Guest]: is a problem, but let me look at it positively. In today's democratic world, Mr. Narendra

02:05:26.240 --> 02:05:31.520
[Guest]: Modi is possibly the most powerful leader. I'm not talking of global power. Obviously

02:05:31.520 --> 02:05:34.520
[Guest]: anybody in America, even an idiot will be more powerful than an Indian leader. That's

02:05:34.520 --> 02:05:40.360
[Guest]: not the issue, but within the polity whose word has the greatest consequences or where

02:05:40.360 --> 02:05:44.600
[Guest]: the greatest power to bring about change. I think Mr. Modi is probably number one in

02:05:44.600 --> 02:05:50.480
[Guest]: the world today. There's an immense opportunity. It may not be recaptured again for a long

02:05:50.480 --> 02:05:58.360
[Guest]: time for another 20, 25 years. I hope, and those who pray, I think we all should pray

02:05:58.360 --> 02:06:03.040
[Guest]: that the ruling establishment will discover the purpose of that power to really transform

02:06:03.040 --> 02:06:07.400
[Guest]: the country because they have this ability. Mr. Modi can change the electoral system.

02:06:07.400 --> 02:06:13.160
[Guest]: He can carry the people with him. He can decentralize power without too much of a discord with the

02:06:13.160 --> 02:06:20.160
[Guest]: legislators. He can improve accountability and service delivery genuinely through instruments

02:06:20.160 --> 02:06:26.480
[Guest]: of law and institutional mechanisms without much resistance. These are very hard for normal

02:06:26.480 --> 02:06:30.800
[Guest]: politicians in normal times to do. Mr. Modi has this, you can completely change the rule

02:06:30.800 --> 02:06:34.560
[Guest]: of law. Mr. Modi and Mr. Amit Shah together can easily change the rule of law. Mr. Amit

02:06:34.560 --> 02:06:38.440
[Guest]: Shah is talking even recently. I was happy to hear that. I hope there is some genuine

02:06:38.440 --> 02:06:43.640
[Guest]: desire how third degree and abuse of power have become endemic in rule of law because

02:06:43.640 --> 02:06:48.680
[Guest]: he sees himself as a victim of that process, for instance. If he really wants it, you can

02:06:48.680 --> 02:06:52.920
[Guest]: actually do something significant about it. And these are huge things. Conceptually, they

02:06:52.920 --> 02:06:57.960
[Guest]: may not be big, but operationally, they are huge things. Here is a priceless opportunity

02:06:57.960 --> 02:07:02.960
[Guest]: where in a democratic system without a Xi Jinping or an authoritarian regime, the leadership

02:07:02.960 --> 02:07:08.440
[Guest]: has the power, actual power to change things with the consent of the people. I hope they

02:07:08.440 --> 02:07:12.040
[Guest]: discover the immense opportunity that's presenting themselves instead of merely wasting their

02:07:12.040 --> 02:07:16.680
[Guest]: energies and enhancing their footprint as a political party and making some more fellows

02:07:16.680 --> 02:07:21.400
[Guest]: MLAs and MPs. I don't understand how that matters. I hope you'll forgive me for being

02:07:21.400 --> 02:07:26.520
[Amit Varma]: glib, but you know, the hope you expressed could also be summed up by saying power corrupts

02:07:26.520 --> 02:07:34.160
[Amit Varma]: absolute power reforms. I, you know, I, I'm a little skeptical about that because we've

02:07:34.160 --> 02:07:40.920
[Guest]: seen the last five years. See, if you don't have faith in human nature, and if you don't

02:07:40.920 --> 02:07:48.280
[Guest]: somehow hope that a leader's sense of glory, ultimately you want to be among the history

02:07:48.280 --> 02:07:54.840
[Guest]: books. If you don't believe that leader's sense of glory could actually be a transformational

02:07:54.840 --> 02:08:01.160
[Guest]: thing for a society, then all political process is about who is in power. I believe that there

02:08:01.160 --> 02:08:06.480
[Guest]: is a immense possibility, and I hope that possibility will be exercised. And I think

02:08:06.480 --> 02:08:10.000
[Guest]: come election time, if you're all disappointed, we'll, we'll vote for or against somebody

02:08:10.000 --> 02:08:16.760
[Guest]: or other, that doesn't matter. But as long as that possibility exists, even as we reserve

02:08:16.760 --> 02:08:22.520
[Guest]: the right to criticize what we believe is wrong and to hopefully correct it, we must

02:08:22.520 --> 02:08:27.240
[Guest]: also be willing to be engaged and see what best can be done with the opportunity available

02:08:27.240 --> 02:08:33.480
[Guest]: today. Otherwise each time, wait for the next election and each time be disappointed. That's

02:08:33.480 --> 02:08:37.120
[Guest]: not the best thing. Many people who are deeply unhappy with BJP today were deeply unhappy

02:08:37.120 --> 02:08:43.960
[Guest]: with Congress earlier, or some other party earlier. So if you're perpetually deeply unhappy,

02:08:43.960 --> 02:08:48.360
[Guest]: if you're not willing to engage and then see what best can be done to improve things, then

02:08:48.360 --> 02:08:53.040
[Amit Varma]: I don't understand what the hell we are doing. And, you know, I totally agree with you that,

02:08:53.040 --> 02:08:57.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, being human, we are motivated by the quest for glory and to leave a legacy

02:08:57.400 --> 02:09:02.720
[Amit Varma]: and so on. But equally, it might be argued that those guys in power right now would define

02:09:02.720 --> 02:09:07.440
[Amit Varma]: glory a little bit differently than us, where they might think of glory in terms of a Hindu

02:09:07.440 --> 02:09:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Rashtra building great statues or temples or, or whatever, which kind of brings me to

02:09:12.160 --> 02:09:18.080
[Amit Varma]: my next question, which is a question about what we are fundamentally as a society, like

02:09:18.080 --> 02:09:22.840
[Amit Varma]: one of the dilemmas that I have had, and I've posed to various guests, and I'd love your

02:09:22.840 --> 02:09:29.320
[Amit Varma]: response on this is that much as you know, our constitution isn't liberal enough for

02:09:29.320 --> 02:09:34.520
[Amit Varma]: me, but it is still relatively liberal. It has liberal elements, but it seems to me,

02:09:34.520 --> 02:09:40.200
[Amit Varma]: and this is a criticism I later found Dindayal Upadhyay himself had made in a different language,

02:09:40.200 --> 02:09:47.360
[Amit Varma]: is that our constitution is a liberal constitution imposed upon an illiberal society. And the

02:09:47.360 --> 02:09:54.200
[Amit Varma]: dilemma therefore, is how can that imposition be liberal? Can you impose liberalism on someone

02:09:54.200 --> 02:09:59.360
[Amit Varma]: because the act of imposition changes it? And is there not something incongruous about

02:09:59.360 --> 02:10:00.360
[Amit Varma]: that?

02:10:00.360 --> 02:10:05.360
[Guest]: I don't agree. I believe fundamentally, Indian society has been always liberal for a long

02:10:05.360 --> 02:10:15.120
[Guest]: time. It's the most eclectic civilization in human history. Whereas did Islam come peacefully

02:10:15.120 --> 02:10:20.720
[Guest]: and survive without too much of strife? Whereas did Christianity come peacefully and these

02:10:20.720 --> 02:10:25.760
[Guest]: are all very early, immediately after the prophets passing, within years, Islam came

02:10:25.760 --> 02:10:33.280
[Guest]: to India. And the Moplah and other Muslims, they still practice without too much of problem.

02:10:33.280 --> 02:10:38.360
[Guest]: Almost within years after Jesus Christ's crucifixion, St. Thomas landed on the Malabar coast, and

02:10:38.360 --> 02:10:42.520
[Guest]: even today, Syrian Christians continue to practice that pretty peacefully. Not only

02:10:42.520 --> 02:10:46.120
[Guest]: practice, but also we learn from each other and embrace. We all know the eclectic nature

02:10:46.120 --> 02:10:53.920
[Guest]: of our civilization. Or Judaism 2000, later on, or Judaism 2600 years ago. I think it

02:10:53.920 --> 02:10:58.560
[Guest]: is part of the Indian ethos, you know, live and let live. And embrace as much as possible.

02:10:58.560 --> 02:11:04.440
[Guest]: And create another God and then pay homage. If Sir Arthur Cotton, who 150 years ago built

02:11:04.440 --> 02:11:09.320
[Guest]: wonderful irrigation projects in Godavari Delta here, and Tanjore, and Tamil Nadu, etc,

02:11:09.320 --> 02:11:13.040
[Guest]: etc. Actually, during his lifetime, he built temples and worshipped. Even today, there

02:11:13.040 --> 02:11:20.800
[Guest]: are slokas chanting mantras about Sir Arthur Cotton. It's a beautiful thing. So I believe

02:11:20.800 --> 02:11:26.280
[Guest]: fundamentally our society is inclusive and liberal with certain huge distortions of caste

02:11:26.280 --> 02:11:32.400
[Guest]: system and many other less than happy practices on account of tradition. But that's true with

02:11:32.400 --> 02:11:36.600
[Guest]: most societies in some form or the other. Therefore, I don't believe that the constitution

02:11:36.600 --> 02:11:40.920
[Guest]: in that sense was an imposition. Actually, it was a reflection of our society. What has

02:11:40.920 --> 02:11:45.720
[Guest]: happened over a period of time is, I think, I'm not a scholar in this respect, I'm only

02:11:45.720 --> 02:11:52.880
[Guest]: a keen student of history. A, we did not realize the various strands of nationalism that operated

02:11:52.880 --> 02:11:59.480
[Guest]: for about 100 years before freedom. And there is a lot of suppressed anger on account of

02:11:59.480 --> 02:12:07.400
[Guest]: non recognition that is surfacing. B, the traumatic, extraordinarily traumatic events

02:12:07.400 --> 02:12:12.240
[Guest]: of partition. I don't think as a nation we have ever come to terms with that. We sort

02:12:12.240 --> 02:12:17.320
[Guest]: of put it away in history books somewhere and a partition happened. Unlike, you know,

02:12:17.320 --> 02:12:22.640
[Guest]: the Germans, for instance, who ad nauseum talk about the Holocaust and what happened

02:12:22.640 --> 02:12:29.460
[Guest]: in Nazism or somewhere else, something else, or civil war in the US, etc. In India, somehow,

02:12:29.460 --> 02:12:34.320
[Guest]: we want to pretend it didn't happen. Well, for me, sitting in Hyderabad or in a village

02:12:34.320 --> 02:12:39.760
[Guest]: in Costal Andhra or in Tamil Nadu, it didn't happen. But I think for a significant number

02:12:39.760 --> 02:12:43.720
[Guest]: of people in certain parts of India, it happened, it's very real, it impacted their lives and

02:12:43.720 --> 02:12:49.680
[Guest]: their ancestors lives and their families. I think by by suppressing it, pretending it

02:12:49.680 --> 02:12:58.120
[Guest]: was not there, I think we did damage to ourselves. Again, there's a payback period. And the third

02:12:58.120 --> 02:13:04.600
[Guest]: strand is, and this is what is disconcerting. Because perhaps of these factors, and because

02:13:04.600 --> 02:13:10.520
[Guest]: the reform movement has disappeared in India, in a religious sense, largely, and during

02:13:10.520 --> 02:13:18.400
[Guest]: freedom struggle, nationalism, enlightenment, reform, they all move together. Somehow that

02:13:18.400 --> 02:13:24.760
[Guest]: we gave up for some reason. Therefore, the most narrow interpretation of the Hindu philosophy

02:13:24.760 --> 02:13:29.160
[Guest]: or religion, they have become now, the most vocal, I don't know if they're the most dominant,

02:13:29.160 --> 02:13:34.680
[Guest]: not yet, I believe, but they're the most vocal ones. You and I, I can speak for myself, we

02:13:34.680 --> 02:13:41.920
[Guest]: can hold many views and still be broadly part of Hindu society. I mean, Charvaka was a atheist,

02:13:41.920 --> 02:13:46.880
[Guest]: and there are many, many others, Kanada and others, etc. We are comfortable with that.

02:13:46.880 --> 02:13:52.280
[Guest]: This is true Hinduism, without losing our moorings or our traditions. But the narrow

02:13:52.280 --> 02:13:56.240
[Guest]: interpretation that happened in the recent past, in particular, because other factors

02:13:56.240 --> 02:14:01.560
[Guest]: that I mentioned, because it's the most vocal one, that is what gives us a tremendous cause

02:14:01.560 --> 02:14:08.040
[Guest]: for discomfort, and the feeling that illiberal Hinduism is there, but I don't think Hinduism

02:14:08.040 --> 02:14:16.000
[Guest]: per se is illiberal. I'm not saying it out of any linguistic pride, but I truly believe

02:14:16.000 --> 02:14:23.080
[Guest]: so. Even as I recognize that all religion, ultimately, is a myth. All religion, because

02:14:23.080 --> 02:14:29.240
[Guest]: I believe it's a necessary myth for the majority of people. Because many evolutionary biologists

02:14:29.240 --> 02:14:35.480
[Guest]: say that religion and faith are hardwired into your DNA. I'm willing to buy that. Therefore,

02:14:35.480 --> 02:14:41.240
[Guest]: we must respect that. But we must also modernize it. And I think Hinduism has been modernized

02:14:41.240 --> 02:14:45.880
[Guest]: significantly and is capable of being modernized further. But that modernization project probably

02:14:45.880 --> 02:14:48.160
[Guest]: is now halted a little bit for the time being.

02:14:48.160 --> 02:14:52.720
[Amit Varma]: You're actually the second person in two days pushing back at my assertion that India is

02:14:52.720 --> 02:14:56.920
[Amit Varma]: an illiberal society. Yesterday at this event where I gave a talk, this friend of mine Vikram

02:14:56.920 --> 02:15:01.320
[Amit Varma]: insisted that India has always been and his formulation was interesting. He said, India

02:15:01.320 --> 02:15:07.440
[Amit Varma]: has always been a liberal society ruled by illiberal states. And I, you know, I agree

02:15:07.440 --> 02:15:13.680
[Amit Varma]: to the extent that yes, we have been very tolerant of diversity, we've absorbed influences.

02:15:13.680 --> 02:15:17.960
[Amit Varma]: I had a great episode on Indian food about how everything we regard as Indian food came

02:15:17.960 --> 02:15:22.920
[Amit Varma]: from outside and we embraced it. Even the elegant churidar kurta that our Prime Minister

02:15:22.920 --> 02:15:28.640
[Amit Varma]: wears is after all, not had its origin in India. But at the same time, I would sort

02:15:28.640 --> 02:15:33.920
[Amit Varma]: of double down on the illiberalism that I believe is there by saying that, look at the

02:15:33.920 --> 02:15:39.320
[Amit Varma]: status of women in India through the centuries, you know, right from our epics till the modern

02:15:39.320 --> 02:15:44.960
[Amit Varma]: day, you know, like you must have read Uganda by Ravati Karve, which, you know, sort of

02:15:44.960 --> 02:15:50.160
[Amit Varma]: looks at our epics of Mahabharata and Ramayana and she talks about the deep level of misogyny

02:15:50.160 --> 02:15:54.680
[Amit Varma]: and sexism in those which are embedded in our culture in a thousand invisible ways and

02:15:54.680 --> 02:15:59.240
[Amit Varma]: it's almost sort of normalized. But, you know, we can agree to disagree on that aspect.

02:15:59.240 --> 02:16:04.960
[Guest]: Let me take this a little bit. Your critique is not of Indian society, but of religion

02:16:04.960 --> 02:16:10.680
[Guest]: per se. There's not a single religion that was not misogynistic and sexist. True. At

02:16:10.680 --> 02:16:17.400
[Guest]: the same time, right from Raja Ram Mohan Roy and Mr. Nitya Sagar and many other reformers

02:16:17.400 --> 02:16:25.320
[Guest]: over a period of time and the Indian society and state the way they embraced. I think increasingly

02:16:25.320 --> 02:16:31.040
[Guest]: the Hindu society, I am now specifically talking Hindu society and Indian society, they're

02:16:31.040 --> 02:16:36.960
[Guest]: recognizing the value of women and I think today things are getting better. I don't get

02:16:36.960 --> 02:16:44.520
[Guest]: depressed about it. My mother could not go to the village to study. She was really bright.

02:16:44.520 --> 02:16:49.320
[Guest]: She is bright because her father said, how can my daughter go to another village and

02:16:49.320 --> 02:17:00.080
[Guest]: study? Today it's unthinkable. And we are more than happy, at least middle and upper

02:17:00.080 --> 02:17:05.200
[Guest]: classes, even the poorer sections to really allow the women to girls to fulfill their

02:17:05.200 --> 02:17:09.960
[Guest]: potential and give an opportunity. There are still serious problems. That's because the

02:17:09.960 --> 02:17:14.440
[Guest]: way we raise our children is terrible. The boys have pampered too much and then given

02:17:14.440 --> 02:17:20.760
[Guest]: a sense of entitlement. And there is a deeper failing in India, and that is education, not

02:17:20.760 --> 02:17:26.160
[Guest]: merely about math and literacy, but it's about the way to think. And I think that is that

02:17:26.160 --> 02:17:33.680
[Guest]: failure that is manifesting today. Because with advancing time, I don't think we are

02:17:33.680 --> 02:17:38.720
[Guest]: sufficiently enlightened because the capacity to think is now diminished because of a horrible

02:17:38.720 --> 02:17:43.960
[Guest]: educational process. But I don't think the society is in general becoming more liberal.

02:17:43.960 --> 02:17:51.400
[Guest]: I reject that hypothesis. Your critique is religion. It's not India. My assertion wasn't

02:17:51.400 --> 02:17:55.680
[Amit Varma]: that we are becoming illiberal. My assertion was that we've always been illiberal and yes,

02:17:55.680 --> 02:17:59.560
[Amit Varma]: the arc of history as Martin Luther King would have said, perhaps does move in the direction

02:17:59.560 --> 02:18:06.580
[Amit Varma]: of freedom and liberalism. But by and large, it would seem to many people like something

02:18:06.580 --> 02:18:11.760
[Amit Varma]: that often seems to me to hold a ring of truth is that what we have in the success of the

02:18:11.760 --> 02:18:17.720
[Amit Varma]: BJP since 2014 is a political expression of our social instincts.

02:18:17.720 --> 02:18:20.880
[Guest]: As I said, some element of that is definitely there.

02:18:20.880 --> 02:18:26.800
[Guest]: It's simplistic on the whole units. I think it's simplistic because if BJP, God forbid,

02:18:26.800 --> 02:18:32.600
[Guest]: does not deliver economic growth and many things that we want as a society, BJP will

02:18:32.600 --> 02:18:37.920
[Guest]: pay the same price that Congress paid. If what you say is true, then it has to be static

02:18:37.920 --> 02:18:43.160
[Guest]: world. Politically speaking, BJP must be sure of itself, no matter what happens, because

02:18:43.160 --> 02:18:49.000
[Guest]: you have a majority with you and they're all imbued by a sense of a narrow notion of nationalism

02:18:49.000 --> 02:18:53.580
[Guest]: and Hinduism. And therefore, politically, there is no further moment. It's end of history.

02:18:53.580 --> 02:18:54.920
[Amit Varma]: I don't think that's true.

02:18:54.920 --> 02:18:58.520
[Amit Varma]: This actually segues very nicely into my last question. I've taken more than two hours of

02:18:58.520 --> 02:19:03.040
[Amit Varma]: your time, and I'm very grateful you, you know, gave me the honor of coming on the show.

02:19:03.040 --> 02:19:08.680
[Amit Varma]: And that question is basically this, that, you know, just carrying on from your assertion

02:19:08.680 --> 02:19:13.440
[Amit Varma]: that if Mr. Modi does not deliver, he will be voted out. But he did not deliver in the

02:19:13.440 --> 02:19:17.960
[Amit Varma]: last five years. And he did get voted in, you know, after massive Big Bang deforms like

02:19:17.960 --> 02:19:23.640
[Amit Varma]: liberalization and the botch DST. And equally in the past, we have seen the watch by government,

02:19:23.640 --> 02:19:27.120
[Amit Varma]: which I thought was a pretty good government. I mean, I, you know, get voted out, unexpected.

02:19:27.120 --> 02:19:32.080
[Amit Varma]: 2004 was a shocker to me, certainly in much of the country. Yes. And I think he's an extremely

02:19:32.080 --> 02:19:38.240
[Amit Varma]: underrated Prime Minister. And my question, therefore, is that, you know, one criticism

02:19:38.240 --> 02:19:41.920
[Amit Varma]: I often make of Modi, and I don't even know if it's a fair criticism, because this is

02:19:41.920 --> 02:19:47.480
[Amit Varma]: inevitable and rational behavior, is that he focuses far more on optics and governance.

02:19:47.480 --> 02:19:51.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, the thing is, the way our election cycles are, for example, there's always a state election

02:19:51.680 --> 02:19:56.560
[Amit Varma]: around the corner, it's natural for a party to always be on campaigning mode than governing

02:19:56.560 --> 02:20:05.120
[Amit Varma]: mode. But a greater worry here is that perhaps they have hit upon this possible truth that

02:20:05.120 --> 02:20:09.720
[Amit Varma]: narratives matter more than reality itself, you know, and that therefore control of the

02:20:09.720 --> 02:20:13.440
[Amit Varma]: narrative is the most important thing. It doesn't matter if you don't deliver in terms

02:20:13.440 --> 02:20:17.600
[Amit Varma]: of governance, it doesn't matter if you carry out something like demonetization, which I

02:20:17.600 --> 02:20:22.120
[Amit Varma]: consider the largest assault on property rights in human history, you still win the UP election

02:20:22.120 --> 02:20:25.960
[Amit Varma]: by a landslide after that, you know, with the economy going the way it is, you still

02:20:25.960 --> 02:20:35.400
[Amit Varma]: win the 2019 general elections. So the larger question there is that, you know, are we given

02:20:35.400 --> 02:20:39.960
[Amit Varma]: that narratives are so important? I'm not saying reality doesn't matter, maybe at some

02:20:39.960 --> 02:20:44.920
[Amit Varma]: point when things get really bad, the narrative changes accordingly. But given that narratives

02:20:44.920 --> 02:20:51.240
[Amit Varma]: matter so much, is our fundamental political challenge, therefore, to frame the right narratives?

02:20:51.240 --> 02:20:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And if so, how has your thinking evolved, not just in the kinds of narratives that we

02:20:57.000 --> 02:21:04.260
[Amit Varma]: need to put forward in our political rhetoric in this course, but also tactically? What,

02:21:04.260 --> 02:21:10.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, tactically and strategically broadly, what are the sort of narratives we need to

02:21:10.000 --> 02:21:15.480
[Amit Varma]: build? And tactically, how do we make those narratives appealing to people? I think most

02:21:15.480 --> 02:21:23.760
[Guest]: democracies have this challenge, and it's increasing a between style and substance,

02:21:23.760 --> 02:21:29.920
[Guest]: be between the tactics required to acquire power and the wisdom required to govern well

02:21:29.920 --> 02:21:36.240
[Guest]: use that power wisely. Mr. Modi has, has been an irredeemable campaigner, is perhaps one

02:21:36.240 --> 02:21:43.040
[Guest]: of the most effective marketing persons, politically speaking, you know, sort of articulate, you

02:21:43.040 --> 02:21:50.200
[Guest]: know, to inspire how to get loyalty and how to acquire power and retain power. But I think

02:21:50.200 --> 02:21:58.000
[Guest]: it's time that the grander purpose, a larger sense of where India is headed, takes a dominant

02:21:58.000 --> 02:22:03.800
[Guest]: role rather than getting your footprint wider. There's no doubt about it. I think many people

02:22:03.800 --> 02:22:08.640
[Guest]: believe that the opportunity is very great, and it has not been harnessed the way it should

02:22:08.640 --> 02:22:14.640
[Guest]: have been. And merely because I market it well, doesn't make the outcome substantial.

02:22:14.640 --> 02:22:20.720
[Guest]: For instance, and I'm saying this with great pain. And it's not about Narendra Modi or

02:22:20.720 --> 02:22:27.720
[Guest]: somebody else's what happened over 70 years. Out of the 49 large economies in the world,

02:22:27.720 --> 02:22:33.640
[Guest]: large economy defined as a country with more than $200 billion GDP. If you take all the

02:22:33.640 --> 02:22:41.720
[Guest]: standard parameters of development and civilization, quantity of water supply, quality of water,

02:22:41.720 --> 02:22:47.960
[Guest]: the sanitation, stormwater drainage, number of years of schooling, quality of education,

02:22:47.960 --> 02:22:52.840
[Guest]: outcomes, infant mortality, immunization, you name it, standard things where data is

02:22:52.840 --> 02:22:58.560
[Guest]: available and authentic by and large. I did nothing extra. I just took the data. I said

02:22:58.560 --> 02:23:07.560
[Guest]: out of the 49 countries, where does India stand? On every single indicator without exception,

02:23:07.560 --> 02:23:17.640
[Guest]: India stood in bottom five. We were never above 45th rank. We ranged from 45th to 49th.

02:23:17.640 --> 02:23:25.040
[Guest]: There were three countries which were consistently in this group of five, apart from India, Pakistan.

02:23:25.040 --> 02:23:29.800
[Guest]: I don't even know why we're fighting. We're doing exactly the same things to our people.

02:23:29.800 --> 02:23:39.880
[Guest]: Bangladesh, Nigeria. If Mr. Modi, I believe he does, wants greatness of India, that greatness

02:23:39.880 --> 02:23:48.040
[Guest]: lies in this. We don't deserve to be in the bottom five. If that, the political system

02:23:48.040 --> 02:23:52.000
[Guest]: understands and we can easily overcome that because we have so many advantages in this

02:23:52.000 --> 02:23:58.840
[Guest]: country, huge advantages, but we're not harnessing them. If that recognition dawns in them, that

02:23:58.840 --> 02:24:05.560
[Guest]: the great India that they dreamt, why did Mr. Modi as a relative teenager or early youth

02:24:05.560 --> 02:24:10.680
[Guest]: gave up his family and everything and did something? There is certainly a deep inspiration,

02:24:10.680 --> 02:24:17.440
[Guest]: Vivekananda, Bhagavad Gita, Hindutva, culture, national greatness. There are some ideas beyond

02:24:17.440 --> 02:24:24.560
[Guest]: individual gain, but if those ideas are not translated into true greatness of this country,

02:24:24.560 --> 02:24:30.600
[Guest]: then I think all of us will regard our lives wasted. I'm sure the leadership in this country

02:24:30.600 --> 02:24:36.360
[Guest]: of all parties, one day wakes up and I hope all of us will make them aware of this.

02:24:36.360 --> 02:24:41.400
[Guest]: So for instance, I don't think people seriously looked at where we are among 49 large economies

02:24:41.400 --> 02:24:46.840
[Guest]: in the world. This is not a groundbreaking story, but we didn't look at it that way.

02:24:46.840 --> 02:24:50.560
[Guest]: We look at our aggregates and we talk about we being the next China or fight in our economy.

02:24:50.560 --> 02:24:56.600
[Guest]: Of course, we are so big. One sixth of humanity will always have 3% of GDP. Even if you're

02:24:56.600 --> 02:25:04.240
[Guest]: doing terribly badly, that is not really greatness. Where are we in terms of averages? If our

02:25:04.240 --> 02:25:10.840
[Guest]: education or school education level is second to bottom, the only country being worse than

02:25:10.840 --> 02:25:15.960
[Guest]: Indian states being Kyrgyzstan, which was fortunately for India included in that survey

02:25:15.960 --> 02:25:20.360
[Guest]: of PISA. And the only response of the Indian government is that India shall not participate

02:25:20.360 --> 02:25:26.720
[Guest]: in PISA in future. And after 12 years, now they decided after, after 10 years that in

02:25:26.720 --> 02:25:32.960
[Guest]: 2021, we'll participate, but only for select central schools and, and, uh, no other schools.

02:25:32.960 --> 02:25:38.880
[Guest]: Are we actually facing reality and trying to change it? Or are we accepting reality

02:25:38.880 --> 02:25:43.280
[Guest]: as it is today and pretending that we are doing better than what we actually are? I

02:25:43.280 --> 02:25:47.280
[Guest]: think this question, honestly, we must all ask ourselves. And I think the discourse in

02:25:47.280 --> 02:25:54.560
[Guest]: the media too, I am equally sharply critical of the media. When did this become an issue?

02:25:54.560 --> 02:26:00.200
[Guest]: Why doesn't it become an issue in a country which is so badly governed? If our education

02:26:00.200 --> 02:26:04.560
[Guest]: or healthcare or rule of law, and the way the basic communities are delivered or not

02:26:04.560 --> 02:26:09.320
[Guest]: delivered our service delivery, those don't become daily issues, badgering us, bullying

02:26:09.320 --> 02:26:14.160
[Guest]: us because this is our life. We face it every day. And if you think some grand power game,

02:26:14.160 --> 02:26:18.320
[Guest]: like a 2020 cricket match, whether Virat Kohli who scored a century or not, if that is your

02:26:18.320 --> 02:26:24.640
[Guest]: dominant issue, then I think the blame equally rests with us as a, as a media and the public

02:26:24.640 --> 02:26:27.760
[Guest]: opinion makers and the leaders in various other fields.

02:26:27.760 --> 02:26:32.160
[Amit Varma]: As someone who works with young people a lot, uh, you know, through the years, do the young

02:26:32.160 --> 02:26:36.600
[Amit Varma]: people of India give you hope because they're responding, they're empowered by technology,

02:26:36.600 --> 02:26:41.200
[Amit Varma]: they're responding to global trends or, uh, are they lost in their devices?

02:26:41.200 --> 02:26:47.920
[Guest]: There is a slice of young people, extraordinary skill, ability, intelligence, exposure, dedication

02:26:47.920 --> 02:26:52.200
[Guest]: and innovation that gives me immense hope. For instance, in school education, the kind

02:26:52.200 --> 02:26:56.640
[Guest]: of things that many people independently independent of the government or sometimes working with

02:26:56.640 --> 02:27:03.480
[Guest]: the government attempting, it's so heartwarming and young people at large are obviously always

02:27:03.480 --> 02:27:08.400
[Guest]: idealistic in every generation. Therefore, again, there is that energy, but the way we

02:27:08.400 --> 02:27:15.960
[Guest]: are disempowering young people by substandard, abysmally poor education, it's hard to reach

02:27:15.960 --> 02:27:23.800
[Guest]: them intellectually because education has failed to replace that through our other kind

02:27:23.800 --> 02:27:27.520
[Guest]: of public communication and to make them think is a very hard task.

02:27:27.520 --> 02:27:31.000
[Guest]: We all have to attempt that, but there's no substitute to improving at least the school

02:27:31.000 --> 02:27:36.360
[Guest]: education to start with so that they can think a little better. So it's a mixed bag. Obviously

02:27:36.360 --> 02:27:40.920
[Guest]: there's hope because younger generation is always more, uh, more idealistic and more

02:27:40.920 --> 02:27:45.760
[Guest]: willing to take risks and they have the future. It's their future that's decided. Uh, and

02:27:45.760 --> 02:27:49.560
[Guest]: there are immensely skilled people and talented people who, I mean, the kind of skills and

02:27:49.560 --> 02:27:54.200
[Guest]: abilities that they have, I cannot even imagine. They are way, way above what I ever was that

02:27:54.200 --> 02:27:59.680
[Guest]: I am in my life. But a whole lot of young people in a country where we pretend that

02:27:59.680 --> 02:28:04.960
[Guest]: we are doing well, they are so denied the basic tools to fulfill their potential that

02:28:04.960 --> 02:28:11.640
[Guest]: even if they have a vague desire to improve things, they're not yet partners in this change.

02:28:11.640 --> 02:28:14.520
[Amit Varma]: Hopefully they'll get there. JP, you're an inspiration to me and I'm sure to many, many

